<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Brussels to increase aid for industrially declining regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Commission intends to devote greater resources to poor and
industrially declining regions, including Merseyside in the UK, and eastern
Germany.
The Commission yesterday adopted a plan to try to arrest industrial decline
as part of the Ecu141.5bn (Pounds 117bn) EC structural aid programme agreed
at December's Edinburgh summit.
The traditional industrial regions of Merseyside, Hainaut in southern
Belgium, and the eastern Lander, or states, of Germany will be entitled to
the higher levels of funding hitherto devoted to backward regions and the
poorest member states. Highlands and Islands in Scotland also qualifies for
the higher funding.
Brussels also wants to reform the Social Fund, devoted until now to training
both young and long-term unemployed, to target part of its warchest to
industries facing structural change. The object is to retrain workers before
they become unemployed - a move seen by some member states including the UK
as a disguised industrial policy.
The Social Fund was worth Ecu7.2bn out of a total EC structural aid budget
of Ecu63bn in the 1989-93 period.
The Commission is also seeking greater flexibility in the criteria for
allocating aid to so-called 'Objective 2' areas, or industrial regions in
decline. The plan here is to channel money to areas which may not now have
high enough unemployment to qualify for grants, but which are vulnerable to
big factory closures.
This more direct attention to industrial restructuring was largely brushed
aside at the Edinburgh summit, when the 12 agreed the 'Delors 2' package on
EC finances for 1994-99. When the package was being put together last year,
the intention was to target funds towards industries like defence,
electronics, cars and textiles, to improve European competitiveness.
Although the emphasis now is on preserving and creating jobs, a row over
whether this constitutes market-distorting interventionism can be expected
when the Commission plans go to the Council of Ministers. A decision on the
whole package, and the dividing up of funding, is not expected until June.
Additional controversy is expected over Brussels' plans to involve workers
and employers in designing the new training programmes. 'We all know this
will be controversial, and I can think of one member state which won't like
it,' said Mr Bruce Millan, EC regional policy commissioner, in a reference
to the UK. In London, the proposals won little favour among British
ministers, who in the past, have resisted any policy seen as 'propping up'
ailing industries.
Mr Padraig Flynn, social affairs commissioner, said 'in the past we've
concentrated on the cure' for unemployment through the Social Fund. 'In the
future, we want to give more attention to prevention'. The focus would be on
retraining workers, threatened by 'new production systems', to maintain
their jobs or help them find alternatives.
endrule
Minister warned over aid, Page 6
</TEXT>
