<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / The Lex Column: Currencies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There is something unreal about sterling's fall to a record low against the
D-Mark yesterday. If anything, short-run expectations of further rate cuts
have been receding. The seven wise men did warn of the risks to the recovery
at the end of last week, and increased loss provisions at National
Westminster could point to persistent economic weakness. But other
indicators like retail sales and money supply growth have grown more hopeful
of late. So there is no obvious reason to push sterling down.
It may be a matter of D-Mark strength rather than sterling weakness. The
Bundesbank could take inflation figures from the German regions, especially
those showing Bavarian consumer prices rising 0.5 per cent this month, as
justification for its cautious response to January's fall in M3 money
supply. Its money market operations yesterday confirm that it is in no rush
to cut official interest rates.
In theory that should spell more danger for currencies struggling to stay in
the ERM than for sterling. Pressure has been returning to the system this
week. Chances are it will intensify and spread as the French election
approaches. But for the time being the easy profits are to be made in
selling currencies such as sterling and the lira which are free to fall. The
UK does not have a political crisis on the Italian scale. Yet there is the
government's Maastricht disarray and its apparent confusion on economic
policy. Paradoxically, the best way for Mr Lamont to stabilise sterling
might be to cut rates to the point where the market knows he can go no
further.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
