<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Observer: In absentia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The problem of how to get rid of a director when you can't find his body is
one of those corporate governance technicalities few company secretaries
have to face. No such mercy, however, for Sean Ryan, who keeps the minutes
for Irish Life.
He was refreshingly honest when Observer contacted him about the departure
from his board of former finance director Brendan Hayes, whom nobody has
apparently seen since last September.
Because no death certificate has ever been issued, Irish Life has had to
invoke a little-known rule by which, if board members fail to show up for
six months at a stretch, they automatically vacate their directorship.
'Tragic though it is, Brendan had to be removed somehow,' explained Ryan.
</TEXT>
