<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Observer: Loadsa dough
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A hundred paper millionaires at a Taiwanese flour-mill are wishing they'd
been faster on the draw.
Last pay day, their wages were multiplied by 10,000 by the computer
crediting their bank accounts, upping their half-month's earnings to nearly
Pounds 3m apiece.
Before most of them got their hands on it, however, the Bank of Taiwan
spotted and corrected the computer's mistake. And even though a dozen
managed to draw out some of the unexpected riches, it was apparently not
enough for them to retire on.
The bank says it is confident of recovering the erroneous payments because
it has arranged for the mill to fire the recipients if they don't repay the
cash.
</TEXT>
