<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Observer: Packing in
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a touch of irony in Roger McKechnie's decision to sell his Phileas
Fogg snack food group to United Biscuits. More than a third of the Pounds
24m McKechnie and his pals are being paid is in the form of UB shares.
Indeed, UB is portraying the vendors as supportive long-term investors.
However, if McKechnie had himself seen the promise of enduring support from
the City, he wouldn't now be handing in his chips. His company, one of the
few success stories in north-east England, needed a hefty capital injection
if it was to expand, and McKechnie was dubious whether City institutions
would stand by him long term.
As for his new UB shares, the 51-year-old stresses that there are no ties.
'I can sell out the day after I get them,' he smiles.
</TEXT>
