<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Breaking point for nerves of steel: German steelmakers are
trying to raise the political temperature over a crisis-hit industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Steel manufacturers are not normally men to mince their words, and German
steelmakers are no exception.
In the past four weeks, the two most powerful men in the German steel
industry - Mr Heinz Kriwet of Thyssen, and Mr Gerhard Cromme of the newly
forged Krupp-Hoesch combine - have suggested that, if European steel
policies do not change, they might pull their companies out of production
altogether.
The question is: are they bluffing? It is scarcely imaginable that two such
giants of the industry, whose entire wealth and reputation was built on the
back of mass steel production, could begin to contemplate abandoning it
entirely. Yet both have diversified in the past two decades and today their
steel interests are a huge drain on the profitability of the rest of their
engineering and trading interests.
Mr Cromme says the question of whether to abandon steel production is
'perfectly realistic'. Of course he does not want to do it, and he is
pursuing all possible remedies to stem his losses from steel production. But
at least he is prepared to entertain the thought.
Mr Kriwet puts it like this: 'If the political establishment cannot or will
not protect the private sector structures in the European steel industry
from unfair competition, then we as entrepreneurs will be forced to take
action - not because we want to, but because circumstances beyond our
control are forcing us to do it.'
Yesterday, more than 10,000 steelworkers from the plants of Thyssen and
Krupp in Duisburg, the grimy heart of the German steel industry, marched to
the so-called Solidarity Bridge across the river Rhine to protest against
the loss of up to 7,000 jobs in their steel town alone. There were calls for
protest strikes, and ringing condemnations of both Bonn and Brussels for
failing to protect the industry. The IG Metall trade union wants a
declaration from Brussels that the industry is in 'manifest crisis', and the
imposition of production quotas EC-wide. The slogan of solidarity was much
in evidence.
The question is: are they bluffing? For it is barely five years since they
were on the streets of Duisburg, fighting (and winning) to save the
Rheinhausen steel plant from closure. Now it is under threat once again.
They know thousands of jobs are going to go: the only question is where. As
for the solidarity, there is precious little in evidence.
The steelworkers of Rheinhausen are competing with their comrades at the
Hoesch steelworks in Dortmund to see which of the two will survive the
drastic programme of capacity cuts which Mr Cromme has ordered. And they are
also acutely conscious that they face cut-price competition both from
eastern Europe, and from eastern Germany itself. Either jobs go in the east,
or they go in the west.
It is clear that both the German steel bosses and their employees are
playing politics in an overwhelmingly political industry. They are seeking
to raise the political pressure on both Bonn and Brussels in the immediate
run-up to today's debate in the EC Council of Ministers. At stake is a
rescue package for the European steel industry in exchange for significant
cuts of some 30m tonnes in production capacity.
The German steelmakers are up in arms because they are facing a new round of
plant closures and mass redundancies, after always being the most efficient,
least feather-bedded operators in the entire European industry. This time,
they believe, it should not be their turn.
Out of DM121bn (Pounds 51bn) in state subsidies paid to European steel
companies between 1975 and 1990, German producers received just DM7bn: the
statistics are distributed with equal enthusiasm both by the manufacturers
in the German steel federation, and the IG Metall trade union. Since 1980,
more than 120,000 jobs have been axed in the German steel industry, or
precisely half the 240,000 cut in the EC industry.
Mr Ruprecht Vondran, president of the German steel federation, believes that
Germany needs only to cut about 5m tonnes of production capacity to bring
its capacity utilisation back to an 'economic' 85 per cent. If it has to cut
capacity according to its EC market share, it will lose more like 9m tonnes.
Whatever happens, he fears that 35,000 to 40,000 jobs may go.
He blames a whole complex of factors - both external and internal - which
have hit the industry simultaneously, on top of the very sharp downturn in
the German economy, 18 months after the rest of Europe slipped into
recession.
On the external front, the EC market has been left wide open to cut-price
east European (and ex-Soviet) imports. 'It was a big political mistake to
open up our market so quickly,' Mr Vondran says. East European steel is
heavily subsidised through artificially low prices of coal, iron ore and
energy.
Since 1990, German imports from the east have more than doubled, from a
monthly average of nearly 86,000 tonnes, to 195,000 tonnes last year: they
account for the largest part of an EC-wide increase, from 240,000 to
370,000, in the same period.
The east Europeans, as well as the Russians and Ukrainians, are exporting,
above all, long products, such as steel girders, wire rods and bars.
'Two-thirds of our problems lie with long products, and only one-third with
flat steel production,' Mr Vondran says.
In a weak market, the east European imports have had a disproportionately
destabilising effect. The US decision to bring anti-dumping suits against 84
importers from 21 countries was the second external blow. Mr Vondran says it
will displace up to 6.5m tonnes of steel from the US market, 600,000 tonnes
supplied from Germany.
Internally, the continual complaint of the German industry is that the EC
reforms of the 1980s failed to stop subsidy payments to grossly inefficient
steel manufacturers. 'Brussels closed its eyes and allowed inefficient
plants to carry on. It was the easy option,' Mr Vondran says.
He cites the state-owned steel producers in Italy and Spain as prime
offenders, and he argues that, from now on, they should only receive
subsidies in direct proportion to the production capacity they remove.
The German industry wants a 'market solution' from Brussels which will allow
the efficient manufacturers to prosper, and the weak to fail. Yet it also
wants more 'social' support to ease the cost of redundancies, and external
protection against cheap imports.
There is also an underlying aspect of the German steel industry which few
inside the country are prepared to face up to. 'The problem starts because
essentially the German steel industry has not restructured in about the last
30 years. That is unique in Europe,' says Mr Jeremy Fletcher, an independent
strategic steel analyst. It may be technologically efficient, but it has
remained fragmented.
He suggests two reasons: first, because the customer base (above all, the
automotive industry) kept expanding; and second, because Germany did not opt
for nationalisation, inter-company restructuring was made more difficult,
especially as there is no tradition of hostile takeovers in the system.
Last year's shotgun wedding between Krupp and Hoesch was the first big move
towards restructuring. In spite of reassurances to the contrary, it now
looks certain to cost thousands of jobs.
There is no doubt that the survivors are hoping against hope that
Klockner-Werke will fail in its bid to write off 40 per cent of its debts,
currently under negotiation with its creditors. Closing down its 3.35m
tonnes production would be a step towards the relief of the industry.
Meantime, Thyssen, Krupp and Saarstahl are talking urgently about
'co-operation' in the long products market. Industry sources say they must
reach agreement within a month, or fall back on in-house solutions: more
capacity cuts. Mr Cromme can scarcely wait. He has already announced the
probable closure of Krupp's long products plants at Siegen and Hagen, unless
they can win a last-minute reprieve from those negotiations.
Yet German steel men defend themselves against charges that they have failed
to restructure. They have just done it a different way, they say. 'We have
diversified, and built up other pillars for our companies to survive on, if
they have to abandon steel,' says one.
Which is precisely why Mr Kriwet and Mr Cromme can make their threats to
pull out altogether, with more than a grain of truth about them. They just
might.
