<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Personal View: How to cure an industry's ills
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROD BEDDOWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European steel industry is in a state of crisis. Western European steel
companies are losing large amounts of money, operating with historically low
prices, experiencing low-capacity utilisation and are involved in trade
skirmishes with North America and eastern Europe. The eastern European steel
industry, like other heavy industries in the east, is struggling to identify
the appropriate structure, scale and operating formula for the future under
free-market capitalism.
This 'state of crisis' has brought vociferous requests for support from
Community and state institutions to aid restructuring: reductions of 30m
tonnes of capacity and 50,000 employees are commonly mentioned.
Conditions in western Europe echo those in the late 1970s and early 1980s
which resulted in a declaration of 'manifest crisis' in the industry and the
famous Davignon plan. This plan was to solve the problem of capacity and to
produce a healthy industry; even as late as 1990, industry leaders were
proclaiming its success. Current cries for help raise fundamental questions:
is there overcapacity in the industry and will its elimination result in a
healthy industry? The answer to the first question is yes, but to the second
is no, unless the industry also adopts a different approach to technology,
cost structure and capital investment.
If overcapacity is reduced now, there may well be under-supply when demand
next peaks. This will lead to new capacity being introduced, replicating the
problem through the next business cycle. Any 'overcapacity' is a symptom of
a disease rather than the underlying cause. The causes can be found by
examining why the steel industry is not capable of making a profit during
this recession.
Integrated steel manufacturers, those using blast-furnace technologies, have
cost 70 per cent fixed and 30 per cent variable. With volumes 20 to 30 per
cent off their peak and prices similarly depressed, losses are made. The
industry is also over-invested. Investment in the last 20 years has
concentrated on modernising technology, increasing the asset to sales ratio,
the proportion of fixed costs and assets in downstream activities such as
galvanising. These investments have pushed the 'overcapacity' from an
earlier to a later stage in the process, on a higher fixed asset base.
Despite a history of cyclicality and limited demand growth, the industry has
invested 30 per cent more than depreciation over the last 12 years.
So how has this progression into a high fixed-cost structure and
over-investment come about? A large percentage of the industry is still
state-owned: Usinor-Sacilor in France, Ilva in Italy, Ensidesa and AHV in
Spain. In the recent past even some of the now private sector companies were
state-owned, such as British Steel. Governments and EC institutions have
provided capital to facilitate the industry's 'modernisation'. These
investments have not been governed by return on investment, except by those
companies which have had the discipline of private sector shareholders.
There is no technological necessity for this over-investment and overly
fixed-cost structure. Many steel companies, notably the mini-mills, have
survived, prospered and returned profits even in the most vicious economic
climates. They have invested in technologies with cost structures that are
70 to 80 per cent variable, and in technologies which are significantly less
capital-intensive, often by a factor of 1:4. This accounts for their health
and the integrated industry's disease. The integrated industry has a growing
plethora of technology options available to it to achieve these costs and
asset objectives. Cheap capital is a cause of the illness, not its cure.
So what will create health in the European industry? The overriding need is
the operation of commercial rules on the allocation of capital to the steel
industry. This will probably be achieved only when there are no significant
assets remaining in state ownership, when plants are less integrated in
nature and when the EC ignores cries for help.
The introduction of capital market disciplines will result in a reversal of
the traditional fixed-cost structure to a more highly variable one and to
lower asset intensity. This will enable the steel industry to operate at or
above break-even in the worst economic climates.
The author is chairman of Beddows &amp; Company, a strategy consultancy
</TEXT>
<XX>
