<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Leading Article: Mr Mulroney's political legacy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRIAN Mulroney is bowing out as Canada's leader essentially for one
reason: to give his Conservative party a sporting chance of retaining power
in the general election later this year. His unpopularity had become so
overwhelming, and so apparently immutable, that its chances of winning with
him at its head were generally rated negligible.
Why is Mr Mulroney so unpopular? Mainly because he has been in power for
eight years, the last few of which have coincided with the longest and
deepest recession in Canada's postwar history. Most of the causes of the
recession lay well outside the prime minister's control, but his policies
have been perceived by many Canadians as making things worse rather than
better. That is almost certainly unfair. It is hardly likely that Canadians
in general would be better off if trade barriers had been left in place
between their economy and that of the US and no attempt had been made to
reform their tax and social security systems. These reforms - the free trade
agreements with the US and Mexico especially - may well turn out to have
laid the foundation for a new era of Canadian prosperity.
The Conservative party intends, in fact, to continue Mr Mulroney's policies,
while hoping that a new leader can escape the odium so firmly attached to
his name and personality. But such a leader may not be easy to find.
Novelty will no doubt be an advantage in itself, as it was for Mr John Major
when he succeeded Mrs Margaret Thatcher. But the Canadian political system,
with its federal constitution, its pronounced regional differences, and
above all its linguistic divide, is more complicated than the British. Not
the least of Mr Mulroney's achievements has been to hold the federation
together, during a period which has seen three federal states in Europe
break up.
To compare Canada with Yugoslavia or the Soviet Union may seem far-fetched;
with Czechoslovakia perhaps a little less so. A bi-national state, in which
the two nations are far from evenly balanced, is almost by definition a
difficult one to manage. The Czechoslovak example shows that democracy is as
likely to drive them apart as to keep them together; that divorce is not
synonymous with violent conflict; and that relations between the partners
are not necessarily easier after divorce than before it. All three lessons
merit Canadian contemplation.
Although Mr Mulroney's attempts at a negotiated constitutional compromise
both foundered - the Meech Lake accord unratified by the western provinces,
the Charlottetown one rejected in a referendum - his efforts, and his
personal roots in Quebec, did help secure a tacit and grudging consent from
the Quebecois to the maintenance of the federation as a lesser evil. It even
seems that, since last October's referendum, some of the heat has gone out
of that issue. There is a danger that the leadership struggle and the
general election may revive it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
