<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Letter: No hold-up on statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr W MCLENNAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Measures to ensure the prompt publication of macro-economic data are at
the heart of the CSO's recently announc-ed package of improved dissemination
practices. In many instances publication times will be advanced
significantly. The first estimate of quarterly gross domestic product, for
example, will be brought forward by four weeks.
There is and has been no question of CSO 'sitting on' results. There has to
be a short gap between our receiving information and publishing it, so that
CSO can add to its value. For example, data have to be aggregated, grossed
up, seasonally adjusted and, most importantly, checked for accuracy and
consistency. As Mr Davies says (Letters, February 24), this type of
statistical information is price-sensitive and important to industry; it has
to be released responsibly.
It is simply not true that information on the latest retail price index is
held back for two weeks; only the broadest of indications about the
all-items index is available at that time, and this is based on partial
information. The concept of a real-time RPI is interesting, and may be
technically possible. But it would not be possible to collect in this way
the same range of items included in the current, monthly RPI, which of
necessity covers practically all the goods and services people buy.
W McLennan,
director,
Central Statistical Office,
Great George Street,
London SW1P 3AQ
</TEXT>
