<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Economic Viewpoint: The Augustinian virtues we need
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Simple horror at the size of prospective UK budget deficits is not a
sufficient reason for adopting restrictive fiscal policies this year. Horror
of government deficits was never the reason why I abandoned card-carrying
Keynesianism - that is the doctrine of stoking up demand until some full
employment target is achieved. The budget of a country is not the same as
that of an individual or a company, despite some partial analogies.
A so-called theorem, frequently put forward, is that, whenever the real rate
of interest exceeds a country's real growth rate, any primary budget deficit
must, if continued, cause the burden of interest payments to explode. (By
'primary' is simply meant the deficit excluding interest payments.) It is
this argument that lies behind the fear of a debt trap and the Maastricht
criterion limiting permissible budget deficits (not clearly defined) to 3
per cent of gross domestic product.
The seven UK 'wise men', who have just reported to the Treasury, range in
their projections of the UK public sector borrowing requirement over the
next couple of years from Pounds 32bn to Pounds 60bn, or 4.9 to 8.2 per cent
of GDP.
The remarks of the seven economists on the overall functioning of the
economy are, however, more interesting than their best guesses about the
level of various indicators in the next couple of years. Indeed I was
delighted to find some common ground with Prof Wynne Godley of Cambridge in
his arguments against an early tax rise or public spending curb.
The view that prospective UK budgets are explosive, and will have to be
curbed soon, would be reasonable if the economy were operating at the normal
rate of utilisation possible without accelerating inflation, and growing at
its trend rate. But this is not the case.
Even if some modest recovery has begun, UK growth is well below its 2-3 per
cent trend rate; and the Bank of England, in its Inflation Report, puts the
output gap - the degree to which demand increases could readily be absorbed
by producers without adding inflationary pressures - at between 2 1/2 per
cent and 7 per cent of GDP. This is equivalent to between one and three
years' normal growth.
The 'theorem' about the debt trap applies in full only if the level of
output is independent of budgetary policy. If higher public spending or
lower taxes cause output to grow more quickly, then the theorem does not
hold. Debt interest rises, but so does the real national income and
government revenues with it.
In a mathematical appendix, composed with a colleague, Prof Bob Rowthorn,
Godley demonstrates that, on certain strong assumptions 'so long as there is
no supply constraint of any kind, an addition to public expenditure would
eventually add enough to national output to generate enough tax revenue - at
given tax rates - to cover not only the initial addition to public
expenditure, but also the interest payments which have been generated by the
additional public sector debt'.
Left to myself, I would merely say, as I did in this column on January 28,
that, even if there is any increase in the transfer burden from servicing
the national debt, this must be balanced against the welfare gains from
higher output and employment.
Godley also has a less abstract argument. The surpluses and deficits of the
various sectors must add up to zero. Let us assume, as a worst case, a PSBR
equivalent to 9 per cent of GDP and a current balance of payments deficit of
4 per cent. Then the arithmetical implication is that of a private sector
surplus of 5 per cent of GDP.
Yet surpluses of this kind have only been approached in the past in periods
of very high inflation such as the 1970s. The only reason for expecting them
now is that corporate and personal saving will for several years remain
exceptionally high relative to investment to work off the debt overhang.
Meanwhile, 'it would be perverse in the extreme to respond to this
exceptionally low private spending relative to income by fiscal
restriction'.
No one who remembers Godley's previous doom warnings on fiscal imbalance
will expect him to grant British taxpayers an indefinite reprieve. But the
Godley point with which I agree is that the time for restrictive fiscal
measures will come when the economy is up against some constraint such as
the balance of payments, accelerating inflation or a shortage of capacity or
labour.
I would, however, go much further than Godley in collapsing these three
constraints into one - that of accelerating inflation. Operationally we
would know we were up against a balance of payments constraint if the
exchange rate fell intolerably or interest rates had to be raised sharply to
prevent this happening. But the only reason for worrying about the exchange
rate is that it is part of the inflationary transmission mechanism.
As far as capacity is concerned, the relevant constraints are not purely
physical, but signs that domestic pressures are pushing up pay and prices.
As the very wide range in the Bank of England's output gap estimate
demonstrates, we cannot know beforehand what the safety limits are. In the
past inflation has started to accelerate even when unemployment has been in
the low millions.
I would not reject out of hand Prof Patrick Minford's view that, because of
the Thatcher government's supply side improvements, the equilibrium level of
unemployment is now down to 1m. But nor would I bank on it in advance.
What would be the main grounds for rejecting the Augustinian view of the UK
fiscal balance - 'God make me chaste, but not just yet'? There is the
extreme neo-classical view that, whatever the chancellor does, tax increases
will be expected by businessmen and consumers and they will adjust their
savings upwards accordingly. In that case delaying tax increases would do no
good, but no harm either.
There is also the ultra-monetarist view that only monetary policy - in
practice interest rates - and not fiscal policy matters for demand
management. But we would have to be extremely confident that only money
matters to disregard the effects of fiscal tightening altogether, especially
when business and consumer confidence remain so fragile.
Another consideration is the anxiety mentioned by the Bank of England that
future deficits might be financed by excessive borrowing from the banking
system and thus stoke up inflation. Fears that fiscal tightening will not
take place when the right time comes cast their shadows in front of them.
Examples are high bond yields and a low sterling exchange rate. To forestall
such fears, Mr Lamont would be well advised to give unorthodox advance
warning of the direction of likely future tax increases and expenditure
curbs.
The final bogey is the 1981 Budget, which raised the tax burden in a
recession, which in turn provoked a protest by 364 economists, but for which
Conservatives active in the period are fighting to claim credit. Because the
economy was, in any case, about to revive substantially the 1981 Budget did
little harm, but little good either. Can one be sufficiently confident of
expansion prospects this time - or the feasibility of further large interest
rate cuts - to risk an early dose of fiscal restriction this time round?
