<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Letter: Late payment - new businesses being fatally
undermined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID REX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Michael Cassell restates much conventional wisdom which, in my
experience, is fundamentally flawed. There are bad payers and would-be
non-payers who warrant heavy-handed letters or nocturnal telephone calls,
but these are a minority.
Most customers expect to pay for goods and services received, and payment
delays are largely supplier caused. Over time I have developed an approach
to improving cash collection performance based on this premise and its
validity is consistently demonstrated by the results achieved. Recently this
was done to dramatic effect (debt more than 60 days old reduced by 95 per
cent) for a company operating in an overcrowded market. In the international
programme I am now leading, my experiences have been similar to those I had
in the UK.
If suppliers take steps to implement efficient internal processes, not just
in the credit department but throughout the sale and supply process, and
manage customer relationships effectively, they can largely eliminate the
causes of significantly overdue debt. This is not down to finance alone.
Success requires the chief executive to secure commitment to the objective
across the full spectrum of the organisation.
David Rex,
David Rex Associates,
131 Newtown Road,
Warsash,
Hampshire SO3 9GY
</TEXT>
