<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Letter: Criticism obscures complex issues faced by UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JAN ELIASSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Nicholas Hinton (Personal View, February 5) is right to be concerned
about the international response to the massive humanitarian emergencies of
the last two years. But his condemnation of the United Nations agencies is
way off the mark and obscures one of the most complex issues facing the
world today.
Humanitarian crises caused by drought or natural disaster are difficult
enough to address in most developing countries. But the crises Mr Hinton
focuses on - not least the former Yugoslavia and Somalia - are infinitely
harder to deal with, as these are rooted in complex and violent political
conflicts. In these crises, it is mainly the Security Council, and not
United Nations agencies, which has the key role in mustering international
resolve and support to bring an end to the conflict, and create an
environment in which humanitarian assistance can be delivered.
The Security Council has, in fact, made a number of historic decisions in
these crises. In Somalia, the council's actions - which included the
deployment of 30,000 international troops - have enabled the international
community to provide substantial relief from violence and hunger.
The troop deployment of December yielded immediate results largely because
UN agencies, along with the International Committee of the Red Cross and
non-governmental organisations, had been striving for some time to establish
emergency relief operations in Somalia. And this was done in an environment
so hostile that relief workers themselves were targeted by warring factions.
Contrary to Mr Hinton's assertions, the secretary-general is undertaking
restructuring measures designed to make the UN more responsive to today's
global challenges, including the need to provide effective emergency
humanitarian assistance.
UN agencies are also seeking new and imaginative ways to improve their
humanitarian response capacity, including the involvement of
non-governmental organisations in humanitarian strategies. But a much wider
effort, with the active support of member states, is needed to establish
effective mechanisms for limiting the human suffering caused by the kind of
bitter, largely ethnic, strife now sweeping the globe.
Mr Hinton's criticism belies the complexity and the dilemma which the UN
faces today. Too many of our staff have sacrificed their lives in the
struggle to provide relief to the helpless for anyone to believe that the UN
does not take its humanitarian responsibilities seriously. Indeed, the UN's
relevance in this new international environment will, in large measure, be
determined by how it discharges those responsibilities.
Jan Eliasson,
under-secretary-general
for humanitarian affairs,
United Nations,
New York NY 10017
</TEXT>
