<DATE>930225
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Arts: Operatic dementia, whirlwind chaos - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORENZO'S OIL (12) George Miller
HONEYMOON IN VEGAS (12) Andrew Bergman
LEON THE PIG FARMER (15) Vadim Jean and Gary Sinyor
UNDER SIEGE (15) Andrew Davis
ROMPER STOMPER (18) Geoffrey Wright
Soaring crane shots; music by Verdi and Bellini; heraldic frenzies of colour
co-ordination; lighting that crosses Rembrandt with Delacroix. Lorenzo's Oil
takes the kind of subject usually reserved for the small screen - a
true-life tale of family heroism fighting illness and medical bigotry - and
nearly bursts a blood vessel trying to inflate it for the large.
In this 136 minutes of operatic dementia from director George 'Mad Max'
Miller, a small but radiant seam of truthfulness is provided by Susan
Sarandon. She plays Michaela Odone, mother of the ALD-suffering child who
gave his name to the rapeseed-derived medication of the title. ALD -
Adrenoleukodystrophy - struck five-year-old Lorenzo in Washington DC in
1983. The disease, which damages the brain via the nerve system, might have
terminated the boy soon after but for the cure-seeking tenacity of his
mother and father Augusto (played by a Nick Nolte involved in his own
life-or-death struggle with an Italian accent).
Michaela and Augusto, hacking through a jungle of 'triglycerides,'
'myelinations' and 'C24/26' fatty acids, finally stumbled on a clearing in
the form of a simple vegetable oil sent for synthesising to a veteran
British biochemist. The said boffin, Don Suddaby, plays himself in the film
and is - no disrespect - a hoot. His walnut face and diffident Northern
burr, at bay amid the Hollywood test tubes, belong in a different movie from
the house-style hyperboles of director Miller, who has not come down to
earth from his last American film The Witches Of Eastwick.
Lorenzo's Oil begins con molto espressione - baroque cathedral ceiling
behind credits, opera booming from Nolte's car radio, hospital corridors lit
like celestial travel brochures - and then moves into maestoso con total
overkill.
A theoretically touching human story, lashed forward by this laying-on of
styles, needs a gentling hand from the actors but gets it only from
Sarandon. She wraps the role so tenderly and completely around herself that
we are engulfed by every close-up. Watch her face as it flickers with fear
and choked-back grief at the first bad news from the doctor. Or watch that
face open like a plant to sunlight at the first hints of recovery from
Lorenzo.
The rest of the cast struggle to keep up. Peter Ustinov is woolly and
unfocused as Professor Nikolais, the family's helper-hinderer from the
medical establishment. And poor Nolte, wrestling with his Italian accent
like Laocoon with his snakes, has some wild moments of overacted or
overdirected emoting on dim-lit stairways and in brainstorming libraries.
Lorenzo's Oil, one surmises, is the right project fallen among the wrong
people. We should believe in the Odones as human beings first, tragic or
operatic paradigms second. And we should beware of any film in which the
stages of deadly illness are nudged forward by Maria Callas singing 'Casta
Diva' or by 'Una Furtiva Lagrima' coercing tears that should need no
coercion at all.
Watching Honeymoon In Vegas is like being dragged off on an unsolicited
holiday, with no time to pack or pleasurably anticipate, and then
discovering that one enjoys every minute. 'No, I don't want to go to Las
Vegas with Nicolas Cage]' - but we do. 'No, I don't want to go to Hawaii
with James Caan.' But when Mr Caan takes us there - he plays a mobster who
has won a weekend with Cage's fiancee Sarah Jessica Parker after humiliating
him at poker - we calm down, stop gibbering and enjoy ourselves.
Film-maker Andrew Bergman wrote Blazing Saddles and wrote/directed The
In-Laws and The Freshman: films in which a touch of frantic went with the
funny. Honeymoon In Vegas is his operation yet. It begins with suave
hilarity in New York, where the world's worst private eye (Cage) copes with
adultery paranoiacs who suppose their wives are sleeping with Mike Tyson. In
Vegas - Cage and Parker jet there for a whirlwind wedding - life is a
sweetly obstructive chaos of gambling disaster, Elvis impersonator
conventions and charming con men. Then the chase is on as Cage crosses seas
and continents to retrieve the prettily twittering Miss P.
Pleasures of the journey include Peter Boyle as a Hawaian chief who can sing
all of South Pacific and almost does; a fussy man buying a ticket at an
airline counter (funniest off-wall vignette since the art gallery scene in
Beverly Hills Cop); and - well, the list is agreeably long, and so is the
charm-and-comedy mileage Bergman gets from the simple tale of a Caan-man
stealing a bird from a gelded Cage.
Every time I tut-tut in print over British cinema's tendency to whinge about
its need for subsidy, a small army of commentators gets purple with
indignation at me. Yet Leon The Pig Farmer was made by Vadim Jean and Gary
Sinyor on a tiny self-raised budget and went on to win the Best First Film
prize at Edinburgh and the International Critics Prize at Venice.
The moral is simple. Talent and determination find cash and win prizes.
While everyone else weeps and begs on the Arts Ministry doormat, Sinyor and
Jean have signed up a fee-deferring cast - Janet Suzman, Brian Glover, Gina
Bellman - and fashioned this cockeyed comedy about a young Jewish estate
agent (Mark Frankel) who discovers he is the product of artificial
insemination. Is his father not the London net-curtain tycoon David De
Keyser? No, he is the north-country pig farmer Brian Glover.
Hearing this news, the entire close-knit Jewish community rears up around
him - a veritable Kosher Nostra - offering outrage or sympathy. And the two
sets of parents, Keyser/Suzman and Glover/Connie Booth, meet at a
Yalta-style suburban conference where they swap accents in a diplomatic
hailstorm of 'Oy-veys' and 'Eeh, lads.'
Jewish film comedy, rampant in America, is virtually unknown in Britain. But
Leon essays the classic mixture of tribal self-deprecation  - like Woody
Allen, the film's hero tries to hide his yarmulka under a protective hail of
WASP wit or suavity - and surreal visions of human togetherness. Just as
Allen plucked Marshal McLuhan out of a movie queue, Frankel is approached by
total strangers in art galleries or petrol stations. In a global village
turned funny-terrifying gossip shop, they know all his problems and offer
instant advice.
In Under Siege Steven Seagal, the action star with the superglued frown,
plays a Navy cook aboard the battleship USS Missouri. One day a bunch of
terrorists come on board and take over the ship's nuclear arsenal. Seagal
tells them to go away, using the following means of expression: an automatic
rifle, a hunting knife, a bomb in a microwave, a private army of fellow
sea-salts still at liberty, and the ship's 16-inch guns. (The terrorists by
now are trying to escape in a submarine.)
I liked this film's insouciance. When the Pentagon calls Seagal by emergency
phone to ask how things are going, Seagal's girlfriend says 'He's in a
gunfight right now. I'll have to take a message.' And headbanded villain
Tommy Lee Jones has time to muse 'I miss the Sixties' between killing
people, having psychotic tantrums and trying to nuke Honolulu. Clean simple
fun, directed by Andrew Davis from a script by JF Lawton.
Why was the press-show print of Romper Stomper so hideous? Processed as if
in blue ink, it makes the 90 minutes of this shock-horror Australian tale of
neo-Nazi skinheads seem like 90 years. At best Geoffrey Wright's film, which
won a succes de scandale on last year's festival circuit, is a fitful thing:
part handheld docudrama of race hatred - the gang-warfare scenes are
violently effective - and part leaden-footed melodrama of romantic jealousy.
But if all London's distributors can offer is this blue-rinse eyesore, wait
for the video.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7812 Motion Picture and Video Production.
</IN>
