<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Arts: Impressions de Pelleas / Review of Peter Brook's
Debussy at Glasgow's Tramway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pelleas et Melisande was once believed to be the quintessence of a certain
type of operatic Frenchness, impossible to rend from gauzy stage settings
and 'impressionistic' musical readings, improperly uttered in any language
other than the original. In recent decades, as Debussy's opera has found its
widely accepted place among the essential masterpieces of the medium, the
process of translating it is no longer deemed either impossible or improper.
In this country Pelleas has had its score theatrically examined under
probing new lights, its play re-located, and its Maeterlinck text
successfully rendered in English.
Each important stage in the process has brought gain and also loss: this is
always the way with essential masterpieces. The latest is marked by Peter
Brook. His Impressions de Pelleas was first played at the end of last year,
in his Paris theatre, the Bouffes du Nord. It then set off on a European
tour which this week reached the Tramway Theatre, Glasgow (a performing
space favoured by Brook, where previously his Mahabharata and Tempete were
likewise given their only British showings).
The translation process is comparable to the one worked by Brook on Carmen a
decade ago. It involves a single setting (designed by Chloe Obolensky); an
unbroken long (100 minutes) act fashioned out of Debussy's five, with two
scenes cut and many nips and tucks (some of them puzzling) effected
elsewhere; multiple casting of principal roles; and removal of all small
ones. The main innovation is that the 'scoring' here, by Marius Consant, is
a reduction for two pianos - one on stage, one echoing it from the side.
The role of the first piano is extended, visually at least. For Impressions
de Pelleas is a Debussy re-location with a difference - to a
turn-of-the-century drawing room out of Matisse, complete with ochre-red
walls, goldfish bowl, orientally patterned carpet and bright chair-cloths;
only two front-stage pools of water suggest any external scenic elements. At
the start the drama is (as it were) announced as a play-reading for friends
grouped round the piano; out of this a 'real' performance develops, which at
the end gently subsides into its domestic pre-condition. So smooth is the
connecting of these dramatic lines newly interlaced with those basic to the
opera that the occasional moment of melodrama - Pelleas's death, fussily
handled - stands out the more starkly.
From all this Brook gains much that is poetically reverberant for his
Pelleas reading. It is partly physical: while the Tramway may not permit the
close focus of the (smaller) Bouffes du Nord theatre, the siting of
Obolensky's spare drawing-room properties in the midst of this wonderfully
rough, untamed theatre space achieves a quietly forceful new grip on the
opera's domestic intimacy and its other-worldliness, its modulations of
darkness and light - and, indeed, on the extraordinary, unrepeatable meshing
of all those states and conditions.
But mainly it is the style of dramatic enactment - candid, serene,
physically restrained yet emotionally intense - that restores something of
the Pelleas mystery sacrificed in too many recent 'new looks' at the opera.
Brook understands that a stripping-away of this sort can elicit a magical
new set of images, signs and symbols to play alongside and against those
already built into the text - a flutter of cloth replacing the games with
Melisande's hair, a darkly lit dialogue around the piano in lieu of the
cavern scene, little Yniold observing everything from beside his chair, a
dead hand trailing in a pool of water.
Because the staging is for the most part so exactly shaped and aimed, a
meaningful new Pelleas experience stirs luminously beneath the old. The main
loss is, of course, the orchestra, that containing vessel of Debussyan
colours, thoughts and feelings - although, once mental adjustments have been
made and preconceptions thrown aside, the constant evocation of the world of
Debussy melodies is itself a source of fascinating new insights. Also, the
very sureness of the domestic framing removes from the opera that
imaginative largeness of canvas that makes it 'about' rather more than just
a family tragedy.
But in Tuesday's opening performance the most significant disappointment -
the only one, in truth - was the discrepancy between the acting level and
the vocal. In the first cast the complete Debussyan balance of word, note
and gesture was achieved only by Roger Soyer's distinguished Arkel and the
pure, shining Melisande of the Korean soprano Jungwon Park (a slight,
beautiful figure of oriental apartness - Brook's alternating Melisandes are
Chinese and Japanese). The others, notably Jean-Francois Lapointe's
youthfully handsome Pelleas and Vincent le Texier's too youthfully handsome
Golaud, tended to blur their musical lines.
Sponsored by Erdman Lewis and Glasgow Hilton; performances until Saturday,
then in Barcelona, Lisbon, Vienna, Berlin and Frankfurt
</TEXT>
<XX>
