<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Technology: The quest for Know-How - Claire Gooding
continues a series on getting the most out of software by looking at a UK
firm's in-house computer system which stores a wealth of expertise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was a time when a solicitor at Linklaters &amp; Paines, the London-based
firm of lawyers, would go walkabout, consulting colleagues in a search for
knowledge. Now, the partners in the corporate department and their
assistants beat a path to one small room.
Surrounded by yellow hanging files and piles of paper waiting to be
processed, a single terminal opens the door to Know-How. This is the
in-house term for a system embracing paper and computerised information
which stores a wealth of expertise.
Information gained from experience is often the most valuable, but it is
also difficult to handle. 'There was a time when the principal sources of
information were a walk along the corridor and the partners' lunch room,'
recalls Barry Dean, director of training and Know-How.
Finding the relevant facts is now easier. Unlike many computerised systems,
Know-How provides a swift route to retrieving facts, rulings and opinions.
The key to this is that the hard work is done by humans. The people refining
the information before its entry into the computer system are as
experienced, and in some cases more so, as those posing the questions.
The custodian of the terminal has become expert at refining the questions
asked so that the computer can search efficiently for the right elements.
Know-How's computerisation is based on software called Kinesis Total Recall,
which uses powerful formulae to retrieve online information, both historical
and contemporary.
'A large part of our work is market-driven. The sort of information our
lawyers need can't be encapsulated in published material. As part of what we
do is to turn things around quickly and to be up to date, we want to capture
the changes as they occur,' says Dean.
Some information is comparatively easy to find and available to anyone using
Linklaters' library. No full-text retrieval system is likely to make books
redundant, nor will the firm ever entirely want to abandon the stroll in
search of an expert.
Know-How has set out to formulate and make accessible a wealth of internal
information. The map references to such information previously existed only
in the heads of experienced solicitors. Now, documents are analysed before
data entry by experts who predict how they are likely to be of use in the
future and encapsulate carefully-coded keywords in the text.
Dean refers to the Know-How systems as an 'experience bank', containing
information on all forms of client work.
'The first cry is, 'Has anyone done this previously?' It's the
identification of the problem that's often the most difficult task,' he
says.
Jeremy Parr, a solicitor in the corporate department who regularly uses the
system, makes it clear the computer is no oracle holding all the answers.
'The role of a lawyer is not just to answer legal questions posed by the
client, but to advise whether a proposal is legally viable. The approach
should always be, 'What is the right question?''
Julie Mackeonis runs the Corporate Mainstream Know-How System, known as
Cormaks. She provides the human link between Cormaks - the first and
best-established of the Know-How systems - and its users, dividing her
duties between answering queries - between 20 and 30 daily - and various
administrative tasks. 'People will come with a broad question. It's a case
of narrowing it down, trying to find the right terminology to retrieve the
right information,' she says.
'Typically, the information on the system is used to shed light on new
situations and interpret them in the light of previous experience,' says
Dean.
It is the experience factor that is important. The money spent on the
computer system pales into insignificance next to the investment in human
expertise. Linklaters has appointed 'information principals' whose job is to
analyse and index the hard-copy material. In the case of Cormaks, the
analyst is Alison James, a qualified lawyer, who now works at home with a
terminal linked to the London-based system, a classic example of
'teleworking'.
The Know-How index contains letters of advice on previous transactions and
situations, opinions of counsel and internal memoranda.
It is vital that the people indexing the data and deciding what should go
into the system should know as much as the people using it.
If James is the architect of the information, Mackeonis, who has no legal
training but some City experience, is very much the curator. Her role is to
know her way around the system and to filter questions so that only sensible
requests are made of the computer. Dave Hall, another information curator
who works in the Cormaks room, has become such an expert on the system that
he is able to do some of the pre-entry analysis himself.
Cormaks is not Linklaters' only Kinesis-based retrieval system. Others serve
the regulatory practice dealing with the Financial Services Act and further
Know-How services are soon to be converted to the Kinesis software.
The human filtering process only takes place for Know-How. Solicitors at
Linklaters are used to having a terminal on their desks for referral to
precedent documents. Corporate mainstream staff also keep close track of
actual stock market transactions.
To get the initial Kinesis systems up and running, Know-How has, for the
time being, been kept entirely separate from the mainstream computing
facilities.
Precedent and practice manuals are frequently updated from the current
Know-How wisdom.
As Parr explains, the system makes available a combination of market
practice, past and present and internal experience. However, Parr and Dean
repeatedly stress that Know-How is only raw material from which to fashion
answers. It cannot take over the 'thinking' part of the job, where the skill
is in interpretation.
What it can do is to ensure the right raw material is readily accessible.
Its other virtue is the ability to provide in-house expertise that is not
available elsewhere.
The system's effectiveness relies in part on people knowing it exists, and
valuing it enough to make voluntary submissions of information. All
Linklaters' trainees receive introductory training. When trainees move on to
another part of the firm where the computerised Know-How system is not yet
operating they miss it badly, a measure of the system's success, says Dean.
The benefits of the system are summed up by Parr. 'It makes the job easier,
gives me a greater sense of security, enables me to respond more quickly and
more helpfully to our clients. In short, it allows us to provide a better,
more competitive service to our clients.'
Dean has reservations about making the system more sophisticated as he
believes neat packaging might discourage hard thinking. 'The documents are
indexed in precise and accurate ways for retrieval. Kinesis has enabled us
to deliver high-quality information in a way that we couldn't before. In the
old days, it was all there in the bulging files, but nobody knew how to get
at it.'
BUZZWORDS
FULL TEXT RETRIEVAL is a database in which an index of every significant
word enables the user to make instant and ad hoc searches of gigabytes of
data. FTR requires an enormous volume of disk space.
TELEWORKING means working at home with a terminal linked to the office.
</TEXT>
