<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Hacker caused computer to 'crash', jury is told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMPUTER system used by an international cancer research centre was put
out of action by a schoolboy computer hacker, Southwark Crown Court was told
yesterday, John Mason writes.
Mr Paul Bedworth, now 19, installed a rogue program into the computer used
by the Brussels-based European Organisation for the Research and Treatment
of Cancer, the jury heard. This caused the system to 'crash', Mr Vincent
Piedboeuf, the centre's head of information technology said. It was the
worst systems breakdown the centre had experienced, he said. Surgeons needed
24 hour a day access to the computer files, which held details of patients
and treatments they were receiving.
Mr Bedworth, of Ilkley, West Yorkshire, denies charges including obtaining
unauthorised access to computer material and unauthorised modification of
computers under the Computer Misuse Act.
The trial continues today.
