<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Estate that is no longer safe as
houses - The housing bill and the Duke of Westminster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO LANDLORD will be more affected by the Housing and Urban Development Bill
than the Duke of Westminster, who owns 100 acres of Mayfair and 200 acres of
Belgravia.
The new law, likely to receive Royal Assent in the summer, will give
leaseholders the right to buy the freeholds on their houses, and will force
the Duke of Westminster to sell property that has been in his family for
more than 300 years.
He views his London estates as the 'jewel in the crown' of his holdings,
which include 10,000 acres of agricultural land in Chester, shopping centres
round the UK and commercial property throughout North America and Australia.
His agricultural estates date back to Norman times, while the London estate
dates back to 1677, when 500 acres of poor farm land was given to the Duke's
forebear, Sir Thomas Grosvenor, on his marriage.
It was gradually developed as Mayfair, Belgravia and Pimlico - the Pimlico
estate was sold in 1953. The Duke has described his land holdings as his
family heritage. 'History undoubtedly classifies the Grosvenor family as
landowners,' he says.
Sir George Young, the housing minister, has described the bill, which has
just passed its second reading in the House of Lords, as 'an essential part
of our policy on extending home ownership.' It has been enthusiastically
welcomed by leaseholders who believe it will tackle problems associated with
bad management of blocks of flats and the difficulties of selling shorter
leases, which cannot attract mortgage finance.
The legislation is particularly welcomed by leaseholders of more valuable
houses with a rateable value more than Pounds 1500 in London. They were
excluded from the Leasehold Reform Act of 1967 (which gave most householders
the right to enfranchise) after heavy lobbying from large landowners, but
will be embraced by the new legislation.
But the legislation is bitterly resented by large landowners, who see it as
an arbitrary transfer of property from one section of the community to
another.
The Duke of Westminster considers that he will not be adequately compensated
for the forced sale of his property, since he will split the 'marriage
value' (the gain in a property's value from putting the leasehold and
freehold together) with the leaseholder. He estimates that some leaseholders
will gain up to Pounds 250,000 by enfranchising.
The Duke says there is principle as well as money at stake. The Grosvenor
Estate says that the proposals are 'a massive infringement of two
long-standing democratic principles' - the right of a private citizen to own
and enjoy private property and the right to uphold contracts freely entered
into.'
The Grosvenor Estate also claims that the new legislation will damage the
appearance of one of the most prestigious parts of London, which owes its
appearance to its scrupulous estate management. 'We are concerned about the
loss of uniform management, the control and enhancement of the urban
environment and the broader benefits to a community an estate like ours
should bring,' he said last month.
The Duke of Westminster's dramatic resignation from the Conservative party
is not the first high-profile protest he has made against the principle of
leasehold enfranchisement.
The first stemmed from the 1967 Leasehold Enfranchisement Act, which
resulted in the sale of 80 houses at a loss of Pounds 2.5m to the Grosvenor
Estate. The forced sale (or 'confiscation' as he put it) of these properties
drove the Duke to take a case against the government to the European Court
of Human Rights.
However, in 1986 the Court found against the Grosvenor Estate. 'The
compulsory transfer of property from one individual to another might
constitute a legitimate means for promoting the public interest,' it said.
This left the Duke unconvinced. Speaking last month about leasehold
enfranchisement, he said: 'The implications of this legislation are
fundamental in a country which has no written constitution and relies on
Parliamentary precedent - because this law interferes with basic liberties
it should send shivers down all our spines.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
