<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / BBC 'could sell channel' to cut licence fee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the BBC's two national television channels could be sold to reduce
the burden of the licence fee, a London conference was told yesterday.
Mr Adam Singer, vice-president (international) for Tele-Communications, the
largest US cable operator, said the released channel could be used to start
a UK version of Canal Plus, the French sports and subscription film channel
which is broadcast over conventional transmitters.
Mr Singer, whose father Mr Aubrey Singer is a former managing director of
BBC Television, said such an auction was just one example of radical options
for the future of the corporation.
Speaking at the FT Cable and Satellite Broadcasting Conference, he said:
'There has been a singular absence of radical thinking and questioning of
not just the BBC's function and purpose, but the justifiable scope of its
activities.'
Mr Singer said the technical forces facing the BBC, particularly new
channels, would make it redundant in its present form.
His Denver-based company TCI plans to introduce more than 400 channels of
television in its cable systems over the next three years, using digital
technology.
In the UK 6.5m homes are expected to have access to multi-channel television
by the year 2000 - about a third of the total.
Mr Jon Davey, director of cable and satellite at the Independent Television
Commission, yesterday released the latest cable television statistics,
covering up to the start of this year.
They show that modern cable systems have 440,162 subscribers, an increase of
65 per cent during the year.
From July to December there was an average net increase of 18,000 cable
subscribers every month.
Mr Davey said he believed there were a number of big new cable deals in the
pipeline.
Mr Richard Dunn, chief executive of Thames Television, said he would be
making an announcement soon about bringing a new satellite channel to the UK
using the Astra satellite.
It would be one of a growing number of satellite channels. None of them on
their own would threaten the dominance of ITV.
'But there comes a point at which all of them, taken together, achieve a
critical mass of penetration, of viewers' time, and of advertising revenue,
so that their economic base is large enough for them to have real buying
power,' Mr Dunn said.
He predicted that critical mass would be reached this year or next.
</TEXT>
