FT  25 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Shephard hints at 'workfare'
options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS GILLIAN SHEPHARD, the employment secretary, yesterday indicated that she
was actively considering extending compulsory obligations on the long-term
unemployed.
Mrs Shephard was giving evidence - for the third time - to the Commons
Select Committee on Employment.
The employment secretary was questioned closely by the committee on whether
the government intended to introduce 'workfare'.
Mrs Shephard said it depended on what was meant by the term workfare. She
said she rejected the idea of a monolithic scheme to be extended to all the
three million unemployed. 'We are looking at a range of options that will
build on what is already in the system,' she said, adding that some of the
changes could be profound.
It is understood that should the government introduce new compulsory
measures for either work experience or training they would be targeted at 18
to 24-year-olds.
A plan to continue to pay benefit for a year to anyone out of work for five
years after they found a job paying more than Pounds 50 a week was proposed
yesterday by Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the social security
committee.
