<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Emu rethink call by Bank official
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Bank of England official yesterday suggested that European
Community governments should look again at the rules they had agreed for
determining when EC member states would become members of the planned
European economic and monetary union.
Mr Andrew Crockett, the Bank's executive director for international affairs,
told the Commons' Treasury and Civil Service committee that the 'convergence
criteria' setting the conditions for entry into the final third stage of Emu
under the Maastricht treaty did not address several important issues that
would confront countries approaching union.
The criteria stipulate that EC member states should have brought their
inflation rates, interest rates and budget deficits broadly into line before
moving ahead to a European single currency and central bank. But Mr Crockett
said countries should also ask themselves whether their economies were
flexible enough for such a step and whether they could absorb economic
shocks such as German unity.
He said he would have welcomed the inclusion of other economic criteria such
as unemployment in the Maastricht package and would like to see countries
consider the question when they review the Maastricht Treaty and plans for
economic and political union in 1996.
Mr Crockett stressed, however, that he was not seeking a relaxation of the
strict anti-inflationary tone of the plans for Emu. There was general
agreement that price stability was important as the basis for sustainable
growth. Expressing his own view, Mr Crockett said he believed that there
were significant advantages in giving 'more autonomy' to central banks to
achieve that goal.
Answering questions from Mr Quentin Davies, Tory MP for Stamford and
Spalding, Mr Crockett agreed that the Maastricht treaty contained the germ
of a serious constitutional conflict in Europe over exchange rate policy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
