<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems in Maastricht amendment
threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTMINSTER skirmishing over the Maastricht treaty took a further twist last
night as Liberal Democrat MPs indicated that they were likely to join with
the Labour party in a fresh attempt at forcing the insertion of the social
chapter into the treaty.
The latest procedural device discovered by the opposition parties centres on
an amendment tabled by Mr Calum Macdonald, Labour MP for Western Isles.
Heightening the possibility of the government being defeated over the issue,
Conservative Euro-sceptic MPs also indicated that they may back Mr
Macdonald's amendment - if it is selected for debate - in the hope that will
it prevent the government ratifying the treaty.
'It's a real wrecker this one, it appears,' said one Euro-sceptic.
However, Labour and the Liberal Democrats argue that if the amendment is
passed the government could still ratify the treaty by bowing to the will of
parliament and inserting the social chapter.
Today Mr George Robertson, the party's European spokesman, will press Mr
Michael Morris, the deputy speaker who presides over the bill's committee
stage, for a full debate on the social chapter itself when MPs resume the
Maastricht bill's committee stage.
Mr Charles Kennedy, president of the Liberal Democrats, said the government
was making a 'complete mess' of the debate over the social chapter. 'We hold
to our determination to see the Maastricht treaty ratified and the social
chapter included,' he said.
Labour has said it will not back wrecking amendments - but has also made
re-inserting the social chapter as its top priority. It won a small victory
on Monday by securing a debate on the government's legal advice
Meanwhile, Tory Euro-sceptics have been encouraged by the succession of
legal and procedural disputes that have engulfed the government.
Mr Macdonald's amendment, which is unlikely to be voted on for several
weeks, would remove Maastricht's social protocol - which includes Britain's
'opt-out' - from the part of the Maastricht bill that increases the powers
of the European parliament.
</TEXT>
