<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lawson criticises moves on ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD LAWSON, the former Conservative chancellor of the exchequer, yesterday
criticised the government for failing to consult the German central bank
before taking sterling into the Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Giving evidence to the Commons' foreign affairs committee, Lord Lawson said
that failure to agree a level for sterling with the Bundesbank ahead of
entry contributed to Britain's forced withdrawal last year from the
semi-fixed currency grid.
'In 1990 there was no agreement of the rate at all,' he said. 'The Germans
had to take it or leave it. That was not a sensible basis.'
Lord Lawson, who was chancellor for six years under Mrs Margaret Thatcher,
said he had reached a tacit agreement with the Bundesbank when he was
preparing sterling's entry in 1985. Thatcher vetoed the move.
When Britain finally joined the ERM in October 1990 under his successor as
chancellor Mr John Major, the Bundesbank thought the level was too high and
was not prepared to support sterling when it came under intense pressure
from speculators, he added.
Lord Lawson, who resigned as chancellor in October 1989 in part over
disagreements with Mrs Thatcher on sterling's ERM entry and other economic
issues, called last September's ERM withdrawal a 'humiliation and a defeat
for Britain'. He said it led to a collapse in confidence within the British
economy, adding that he would agree with pundits who dubbed the day 'Black
Wednesday'.
</TEXT>
