<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Battersea deal raises questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Simon Haywood, director of finance at Wandsworth Council, said last night
the council was in the dark about the nature of negotiations over the sale
of Battersea Power Station involving a Hong Kong property family.
He said: 'We hope to have meetings in the next few days with the parties
concerned to establish who exactly we are dealing with.'
The Hong Kong brothers negotiating to acquire Battersea Power Station and
its 31-acre site in south London said yesterday that they would start by
buying the bank debt on the development.
The debt deal, expected to be concluded within the next few days, will be
the first stage in gaining overall control of the site, which is owned by
Battersea Leisure, a company controlled by Mr John Broome, the property
developer and theme-park owner.
Mr George and Mr Victor Hwang - the brothers who also go under the name
Wong, the western equivalent of their name - will in effect become Mr
Broome's lenders on the site which they will then be able to claim as
collateral for loans which are in default.
The size of the debt has not been disclosed but with interest it is likely
by now to be more than Pounds 100m.
The banking syndicate led by Bank of America is likely to be selling the
debt at a considerable discount.
How or when the transfer of the site to the Hwangs will happen is not yet
clear. It is understood that Mr Broome's role in the development is unlikely
to continue for long although a decision on his role has not yet been made.
Mr Broome has just over a week to appeal against a court decision taxing him
for an estimated Pounds 20,000 in legal costs involved in the council's
legal pursuit of Pounds 170,000 owed on overdue building fees.
The sum of Pounds 170,000 was agreed to in an out-of-court settlement by all
the parties concerned last summer but remains unpaid.
Mr Guy Senior, chairman of the council's planning committee, said that over
the past month the issue has been the subject of renewed correspondence and
meetings between Mr Broome and the council.
Mr Senior said: 'We have made it clear that if we do not receive the money
we are owed we shall seek to have a statutory order served on the company
and have it declared insolvent.'
</TEXT>
