<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Irish ask for probe on plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Irish government has asked the European Commission to investigate claims
that Britain breached EC competition rules by offering incentives to keep
open a computer manufacturing plant at Ayr in south-west Scotland.
Dublin says the incentives - in the form of public procurements and state
aids - have been offered to Digital Equipment, the US computer manufacturer,
which is to decide this week whether to concentrate production at the Ayr
plant, or at a similar one at Galway in the west of Ireland. The Ayr plant
employs 980, the Galway one 1,100.
On Tuesday Mr Padraic MacKernan, Ireland's ambassador to the EC, delivered
letters to both Mr Karel Van Miert, the EC competition commissioner, and Mr
Renie Vanni d'Archirafi, the EC commissioner for the internal market, asking
them to investigate whether the incentives offered by the UK government to
Digital had breached EC competition rules.
Ireland's department of enterprise and employment said yesterday the request
did not yet constitute a formal complaint to the EC, as hard evidence was
lacking. The request was being made on the basis of media reports out of
Scotland 'and information which has emanated from non-media sources in
Britain and Scotland'.
The Scottish Office refused yesterday to comment beyond saying it was a
matter between the Irish government and the commission.
Any question of support for Digital's European reorganisation would be
subject to the normal EC rules on state aid, it added.
Scottish Enterprise, the development body, said it had 'no difficulty with
any investigation'.
</TEXT>
