<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Consortium at Lloyd's formed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CASSIDY DAVIS, the Lloyd's managing agency, has formed an underwriting
'consortium' with two of France's largest insurance companies, allowing it
to underwrite an extra Pounds 12m of business.
The agreement, the first by any Lloyd's syndicate since rules governing such
arrangements were eased last year, allows the underwriter of Cassidy Davis
syndicate 582 to accept the extra business on behalf of Assurance Generales
de France and SCOR.
Two brokers, Hayward Till and Jardine Thompson Graham, are also involved in
the deal, which is geared to increasing sales of creditor insurance -
accident, sickness and unemployment cover for loans.
Consortia between syndicates and insurance companies are one of the main
ways that extra capital can be brought to the Lloyd's market, where
insurance capacity has shrunk following recent heavy losses.
Capital is expected to fall to less than Pounds 8.5bn in 1993, compared with
Pounds 10.1bn in 1992, owing to the fall in the number of Names -
individuals whose capital supports Lloyd's.
'It gives us the capacity we need in an expanding market,' said Mr Tony
Cassidy, chairman of Cassidy Davis.
</TEXT>
