<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Ministers warned over Pounds 1bn EC aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRUCE Millan, EC regional policy commissioner, yesterday confirmed the UK
risked losing 'large' sums of Community aid for depressed regions unless it
conformed to rules obliging member states to match Community funds.
The commissioner has written to the British government seeking urgent talks
following complaints from local authorities in the nine UK regions eligible
for regional aid grants.
Senior commission officials confirmed that up to Pounds 1bn earmarked for
the UK has still to be disbursed - and could be lost if not committed to
regional development schemes by the end of this year. 'If they don't want to
lose the money they will have to do something about it,' Mr Millan said,
although he added: 'Nobody is suggesting that they're going to lose
everything.'
The Department of Trade and Industry sought to play down the row saying
funds would be matched - although final details have still to be agreed.
The government came under attack, however, from Mr Derek Fatchett, Labour
industry spokesman. In a letter to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, he said: 'It would be beyond the comprehension of the British
public if, at a time of mounting unemployment, the actions of the British
government deprived some of our most disadvantaged regions of EC regional
aid.'
The UK was assigned Ecu2.6bn (Pounds 2.14bn) in 1989-93 for the for the nine
'industrially declining' regions, ranging from Merseyside to Tyneside. At
the end of last year Ecu1.91bn had been committed to development programmes
in these regions, leaving Ecu691m for 1993. But by the end of last year only
Ecu1.37bn had been distributed by Brussels, partly, a commission official
confirmed, because of the 'matching funds' dispute. A total of Ecu1.23bn is
still outstanding.
Under EC rules community help for depressed regions must be matched by
funding to local authorities provided by governments. Under UK practice all
EC money is channelled through the Treasury. Brussels insists this means
ineligible regions get some of it, and those which are eligible do not get
their entitlement.
The EC funds 'cannot just go into a Treasury pot,' Mr Millan said yesterday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9531 Housing Programs.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government spending.
