<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Council reporting rules may change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITIES will be required to maintain registers of all their fixed
assets for the first time under new reporting rules proposed by the
Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy.
In guidelines circulated this week the institute calls for an accounting
system that shows most fixed assets in councils' balance sheets at current
cost. The system would require all authorities to identify their assets and
have them regularly revalued.
The proposals are open to consultation until April 19 and are expected to be
endorsed by the Accounting Standards Board. They would become mandatory for
the 1994-95 financial year.
Mr John Scotford, the treasurer of Hampshire county council and chairman of
the committee which produced the proposals, said: 'The capital side of local
authority accounting just doesn't stand up to any kind of examination. It
does not attempt to show their worth or how they use their assets.'
The institute estimates that the one-off cost of the change would be Pounds
7m across England, Wales and Scotland, while further revaluations would
amount to Pounds 1m each year.
