<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Councils' reporting rules may change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITIES will be required to maintain registers of all their fixed
assets for the first time under sweeping new reporting rules proposed by the
Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy.
In guidelines circulated this week, the institute calls for an accounting
system that shows most fixed assets in councils' balance sheets at current
cost.
The system would require all authorities to identify the assets they hold
and have them regularly revalued, at least every five years.
The proposals are open to consultation until April 19 and are expected to be
endorsed by the Accounting Standards Board this summer. They would become
mandatory for the 1994-95 financial year.
Mr John Scotford, treasurer of Hampshire county council and chairman of the
institute committee which produced the proposals, said: 'The capital side of
local authority accounting just doesn't stand up to any kind of examination.
It does not attempt to show their worth or how they use their assets.'
Local authorities have traditionally presented their accounts with the
emphasis on how assets are financed.
They have long resisted the move towards capital accounting primarily
because of fears about the costs of changing their systems.
The institute estimates that the one-off cost of change would be Pounds 7m
across England, Wales and Scotland, while further revaluations would amount
to Pounds 1m each year.
The new standards are an essential step in extending contracting-out of
local authority work to white-collar services. Town hall functions such as
architecture, planning and local tax collection could be contracted out
under legislation passed before the general election.
These functions cannot be subject to competitive tendering until councils
have introduced internal trading accounts which make costs more transparent.
Sharing overheads between different functions and the valuation of fixed
assets will be central.
The value of the assets has a further importance to the in-house team if
they are bidding against outside contractors for their work. With services
already subject to competitive compulsory tendering, the in-house team must
make a 5 per cent return on capital employed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
