<DATE>930225
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / US budget set to enter realm of realism: Vision of Change
may have to
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration must be delighted by the reaction of the US bond
market to the economic package unveiled last week. The stunning decline in
long yields - to well under 7 per cent - potentially provides a far more
important boost to growth than Mr Clinton's so-called short-term economic
stimulus.
But the package is selling less well on Capitol Hill, where many
conservative Democrats worry that the emphasis on tax increases and new
spending programmes could prove a political liability. And, unlike the bond
market, the Washington think-tank community is far from convinced that the
budgetary austerity promised towards the end of Mr Clinton's term will prove
sufficient to get the deficit under control.
Mr Leon Panetta, the budget director, promised a package without the
customary 'smoke and mirrors'. He only partially succeeded. One of the most
misleading aspects of the plan is the claimed Dollars 30bn (Pounds 21.1bn)
short-term stimulus. What the administration has really done is draw a
circle around some of the measures and call that a stimulus; other measures
that will reduce demand, such as the rise in personal tax rates backdated to
January 1 this year, are excluded from these calculations.
The final table on the last page of A Vision of Change for America gives the
game away. This shows that policy changes will increase the structural
budget deficit (the deficit adjusted for the business cycle) by a negligible
Dollars 12.7bn in fiscal 1993 and reduce it by no less than Dollars 38.9bn
in fiscal 1994. In other words, fiscal policy will be contractionary to the
tune of Dollars 26.3bn over the next two years; the stimulus is thus almost
entirely an illusion, which is one reason, of course, why bond prices are
soaring.
In Washington, however, the main focus is on longer-term measures. 'The plan
does not solve the deficit problem once and for all. We will have to return
to this,' says Mr Rudolph Penner, economics director at accountants KMPG
Peat Marwick and a former head of the Congressional Budget Office.
Mr Gene Steuerle, a former senior Treasury official now at the Urban
Institute, agrees. He says it is useless to pretend that a great deal of
deficit reduction can be achieved with a package that limits significant
spending cuts to defence and significant tax increases to the affluent. 'A
Dollars 150 energy tax is not a solution when you have a deficit per
household of Dollars 3,000 a year.'
The table showing changes in the structural budget deficit illustrates how
limited the administration's goals really are. Whereas past deficit-cutting
packages aimed to eliminate the structural deficit, the Clinton team is not
even trying to get it below Dollars 200bn, or close to 3 per cent of GDP.
After the election Mr Clinton said he would get the ratio of debt to GDP
back on a declining trend. Mr Steuerle's calculations, however, show the
debt/GDP ratio rising steadily - from 53.5 per cent this year to 56.6 per
cent in 1998.
The balance of the Clinton package is being attacked on several grounds. The
Centre for Strategic and International Studies points out that the plan
calls for Dollars 3-Dollars 4 of tax increases for every Dollars 1 of net
spending cuts. That compares with a ratio of Dollars 2.75 in spending cuts
for every Dollars 1 in tax increases advocated in a bipartisan
budget-cutting plan published by the centre last year.
But while sensitive to this argument, many Democrats also worry about the
timing of tax and spending changes. Tax increases take effect this year and
next, but significant spending reductions are delayed until after
congressional elections at the end of 1994.
Too often in the past spending cuts scheduled three or four years down the
road have failed to materialise.
The sheer momentum of spending programmes should not be under-estimated. The
Bush administration wanted to control spending, but over its four years
federal outlays actually rose 29 per cent in cash terms - in spite of a
sharp fall in real spending on defence.
The Clinton team is recommending Dollars 160bn of investment incentives and
new programme spending in areas such as infrastructure, education and
technology, yet projecting a total increase in federal outlays over four
years of only about 15 per cent - half the increase under President Bush.
Since spending on entitlement programmes is expected to rise by more than 20
per cent, the overall restraint is achieved only by projecting zero growth
over four years in discretionary programmes. Even allowing for deep defence
cuts, critics wonder if that is feasible.
There are also doubts about the revenue projections: the increase of roughly
one-third in marginal tax rates on wealthy individuals and on unincorporated
small business may lead to increased use of tax shelters and lower than
expected receipts.
Even allowing for faster economic growth than factored for in budget
projections, the view of many Washington experts is that Mr Clinton may have
to scale back his planned spending increases and investment incentives to
make his deficit-cutting package fully credible. In a reverse of historical
precedent it could just be that new members of Congress - the Ross Perot
class of 1992 - will force the president to be more realistic.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
                    CHANGE IN THE STRUCTURAL DEFICIT
                       (Fiscal years, Dollars bn)
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
                                               Estimate
                              1993   1994   1995   1996   1997   1998
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Baseline deficit             319.2  301.3  285.9  297.0  346.3  389.7
Cyclical component            68.8   51.6   36.3   24.0   16.8   16.1
Deposit insurance              6.9    7.9   -4.0  -12.5  -11.3   -7.3
Baseline structural deficit  245.5  241.8  263.6  285.5  340.8  380.9
Effect of policy proposals    12.7  -38.9  -54.2  -91.7 -139.8 -148.3
Proposed structural deficit  258.2  202.9  209.4  193.8  201.0  232.6
Debt/GDP (%)                  53.5   54.8   55.5   55.7   55.9   56.6
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Clinton plan and Urban Institute
