<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Illness casts doubt over defence secretary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR LES ASPIN, the US defence secretary, remained in hospital yesterday with
heart problems and may have to reduce his workload when he is eventually
released, according to his aides.
Mr Aspin was taken to hospital on Sunday night suffering from acute
shortness of breath triggered by a reaction to a typhoid inoculation. He is
expected to make a complete recovery.
Nevertheless, his illness has amplified concerns about the vacuum of power
at the Pentagon, where Mr Aspin is the only senior official to have been
appointed so far by President Bill Clinton.
Mr William Perry, who has been nominated to be deputy secretary, has not yet
been confirmed by the Senate, and the acting secretary in Mr Aspin's absence
is a 'caretaker' left over from the Bush administration.
Mr Aspin's former colleagues in Congress had already begun, before his
illness, to criticise the slowness with which he has filled top positions at
the Pentagon. One member of the Armed Services Committee, which Mr Aspin
chaired for nine years, said he was more alone than General Custer at the
battle of the Little Big Horn.
In the hurry to produce a defence budget by the administration's March 23
deadline, Mr Aspin has already been forced to content himself with makeshift
cuts from the baseline proposed by his predecessors in the Bush
administration, rather than rethinking the missions and structures of the US
armed forces from the bottom up.
Mr Aspin had spent a 'good night' in hospital, according to an aide
yesterday, but it was not clear when he would be released.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9711 National Security.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
