<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Angolan president dismisses minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUANDA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANGOLAN President Jose Eduardo dos Santos announced yesterday that he was
dismissing his finance minister and central bank governor following a
controversial move to narrow the gap between the official and black market
exchange rates, Reuter reports from Luanda.
A note from his office said minister Salamao Xirimbimbi and bank governor
Sebastiao Lavrador would be replaced temporarily by former planning minister
and current trade minister Emanuel Carneiro and deputy central bank governor
Generoso de Almeida.
The note did not detail reasons for the move. However, analysts said the
decision appeared to be linked to a controversial move several weeks ago to
abandon the official unrealistic exchange rate of 580 kwanzas to the dollar
and peg it closer to the black market rate.
The official rate, which covered some transactions including imports by
state bodies, was adjusted to 7,000 kwanzas to the dollar.
The move, which made the prices of some imported goods and services soar,
provoked criticism by local businessmen as well as some parliamentarians.
The black market rate jumped back to around 10,000 kwanzas after falling
back initially.
