<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Keating promises review of monarchy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA'S Labor government yesterday promised to establish a committee to
draw up plans for constitutional reform if it wins the federal election on
March 13.
Mr Paul Keating, the prime minister, said the committee would be asked to
produce options for the creation of a federal republic to replace the
existing constitutional monarchy. The undertaking, delivered at the formal
launch of Labor's election policies, represents the party's first move
towards the implementation of its decade-old commitment to the abolition of
the monarchy.
Mr Keating said Australians were beginning to question the relevance of the
1901 constitution under which Australia's head of state is the British
monarch. He said Australians should decide whether to abolish the monarchy
before 2001, the centenary of the federation of the continent's six former
British colonies.
However, he did not commit Labor to a referendum during the three-year life
of the next parliament.
Abolition of the monarchy is opposed by the Liberal/National party
opposition, which is leading the government by between 6 and 12 percentage
points in the opinion polls.
Mr Keating also promised extra spending of about ADollars 300m (Pounds
142.8m) on social benefits for low-income families, but the low-key policy
launch appeared unlikely to revitalise the government's flagging campaign.
Ralph Atkins adds: In London the Foreign Office refused to be drawn on the
issue. 'It is absolutely a matter for the Australians,' said an official.
Buckingham Palace also refused to comment.
Editorial comment, Page 23
