<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Kim - reformer or political prisoner?: South Korea watches
and waits as delicate balancing act takes shape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE are two contrasting images of Mr Kim Young-sam, who will be
inaugurated today as South Korea's first civilian president since 1961.
One is the courageous dissident who challenged the country's military
dictatorship for almost three decades and saw his efforts rewarded with the
introduction of democracy in 1987.
The other is the skilful, and his critics would say opportunistic,
politician who abandoned the opposition in 1990 and joined his former
adversaries in the ruling party. The defection, which gave the ruling party
a parliamentary majority, eventually earned him the nomination as the
government candidate in the December presidential election.
The main question surrounding Mr Kim is whether his reformist tendencies
will predominate during his single five-year term, or will he be beholden to
the conservative political interests that helped elect him president.
Mr Kim is well aware of the contradiction. His campaign slogan was 'reform
amid stability' and his recent appointments reflect the delicate balancing
act he must perform.
Reformers were named to his personal staff in the Blue House, the executive
mansion, while conservative politicians are expected to hold most of the
cabinet postions under Prime Minister Hwang In-sung, a former general and
cabinet minister during the military dictatorship.
In many respects, Mr Kim's policies differ little from those of his
predecessor, Mr Roh Tae-woo. In foreign affairs, for example, he is expected
to maintain a tough stance against North Korea until it resolves suspicions
about its possible development of nuclear weapons.
The changes he proposes include making the government more accessible to the
public and removing the last vestiges of its authoritarian past. Mr Kim
would curb the power of the National Security Planning Agency, the
intelligence agency that harassed him and other dissidents during military
rule.
Another goal is to fight the corruption that plagues the government,
although that has also been promised by previous administrations to little
effect. The personal assets of senior officials, for example, will be
audited. One aspect of the anti-corruption campaign is the investigation of
bribes and illegal election funding by the country's large industrial
conglomerates, or chaebol, to gain business favours from the officials who
closely regulate the economy.
Partisan considerations, however, have apparently been a factor in recent
probes, which have focused on chaebol that opposed Mr Kim last year. Most
prominent has been the investigation of Hyundai and Mr Chung Ju-yung, its
founder, who stood against Mr Kim in the presidential election. Other
companies now under tax investigation for possible misuse of funds are
Pohang Iron and Steel and Daewoo Corporation, whose leaders also criticised
Mr Kim.
The new president, however, has dismissed speculation that he will dismantle
the chaebol in response to popular feeling against them. The public
considers the chaebol an obstacle to social equality because of their
economic dominance and the past favours granted to them at the expense of
the small business sector.
Indeed, Mr Kim has criticised as ineffective the credit restrictions imposed
by President Roh on the chaebol to curb their growth. He believes a radical
restructuring of Korea's industrial structure would harm the country's
economic performance, particularly when the nation is undergoing a difficult
transition phase from being a low-cost producer of bulk goods to a high-tech
manufacturer.
Instead, Mr Kim hopes to promote the chaebol's gradual dissolution by
enforcing anti-trust laws. Family ownership of these industrial groups would
be weakened by tougher inheritance taxes and the listing of all chaebol
subsidiaries, many of which are now privately held, on the Seoul bourse.
A key ingredient would also be deregulation, chiefly through reform of the
financial system, which remains the government's chief instrument in
managing the economy.
The government is expected to announce extensive financial liberalisation
next month and proposals for restructuring the inefficient banking sector
and other financial institutions by June.
But Mr Kim could face a hard time in implementing these changes since they
represent a loss of power for the bureaucracy and the political
establishment.
Mr Kim's advisers in the Blue House appear firmly committed to reform, but
he still must appease the conservatives within the ruling Democratic Liberal
party.
Whether Mr Kim has the strength and perseverance to push through the reforms
remains to be seen.
</TEXT>
