<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Somalis killed by US troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE, Africa Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US TROOPS in Somalia killed at least nine people during rioting in the
Somali capital of Mogadishu yesterday by supporters of warlord Mohamed Farah
Aideed.
The outbreak of anti-US rioting may well mark the point at which things
start to go badly wrong for America's precedent-setting humanitarian
intervention. In the view of a rising number of Somalis, the US presence is
rapidly changing from an army of liberation into a force of occupation.
As in Lebanon in the early 1980s the US has inevitably come to be seen as a
partial player in the labyrinthine and vicious world of Somalia's rival
clan-based militias. Washington's authority and its willingness to use
greater force against armed gangs and bandits is being severely tested by
the armed factions.
The nine rioters shot dead were among thousands of protesters who erected
barricades of burning car tyres in the city and tried to storm the US and
French embassies.
The demonstrators - loyal to Gen Aideed, Somalia most powerful warlord  -
who two months ago thronged the streets to welcome US marines yesterday
chanted 'Go Home Americans' and 'Down with America'.
Angered about what they believe is US support for a rival warlord, the
protesters fought running battles with foreign troops.
The latest violence erupted after the clan-based militia led by Gen Mohamed
Siad Hersi 'Morgan,' the son-in-law of former dictator Gen Mohamed Siad
Barre, seized part of the southern port city of Kismayo from an ally of Gen
Aideed. Belgian and US troops stood by amid the clan fighting which claimed
at least 11 lives and left the city destabilised.
Despite a US ultimatum accusing Gen Morgan of criminal activities and
warning him to evacuate his forces from the city by midnight tonight, Gen
Aideed went on radio accusing the US of bias towards Gen Morgan. 'We don't
want a jihad (holy war) but events in the last few days are very
disturbing,' he said, threatening action unless the US stopped supporting
Gen Morgan.
The fighting in Kismayo, and inaction by the foreign forces, is a serious
blow to the operation. It has proved that the warlords remain highly armed,
powerful and determined to carry on with their conflict.
It has also exposed the lack of will among the US-led force to use their
superior firepower.
Memories of Beirut, where US marines had to beat an inglorious retreat in
1983 after a suicide bomber killed 242 troops, and of Vietnam continue to
cast a dark cloud over the US military intervention. US generals are anxious
not to take risks that might result in hefty casualties.
Political observers, however, say it was inevitable the US would get sucked
into the scheming and complex world of Somali politics it does not
understand.
</TEXT>
