<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / German inflation turns downwards: Figures raise hopes of
another Bundesbank cut in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEST GERMAN inflation has turned downwards again, encouraging fresh
speculation that the Bundesbank may further reduce lead interest rates as
early as next Thursday.
Preliminary figures from two key states, published yesterday, show the rate
of consumer price increases has slowed from 4.4 per cent in January to
around the 4.2 per cent forecast by most economists. Coupled with the
unexpected contraction in money supply growth in January and German
industry's accelerating plunge into recession, the news could encourage the
central bankers to reduce rates further.
Conditions for more cuts have improved since the Bundesbank's surprise
reductions earlier this month.
On February 4, after further tensions in the European exchange rate
mechanism, it reduced the discount rate by 0.25 of a point to 8 per cent and
the internationally sensitive Lombard rate by half a point to 9 per cent.
Since then Germany's public sector unions have accepted a 3 per cent pay
increase for this year, sending a clear signal that pay-driven inflation is
coming under control.
Following last week's news that last year's rapid growth in the M3 money
supply measure had not only slowed but fallen in January, economists have
revised their forecasts and believe M3 will stay within the Bundesbank's
target range for the rest of this year.
Political pressure on the bank is also continuing to protect the core of the
European monetary system by helping to protect the French franc.
Mr Ulrich Cartellieri, a director of the Deutsche Bank, yesterday stressed
the importance of defending the franc while at the same proceeding with an
orderly reduction in interest rates.
At each successive meeting the central bank council had come under increased
market pressure to reduce lending rates significantly, he wrote in an
article in Die Zeit.
The principal obstacles in the way of marked reductions remain inflation and
lingering doubts about the government's ability to deliver swingeing public
spending cuts and reduce the national deficit.
The Bundesbank wants the annual rate of consumer price increases down to 2
per cent, but the hard core of inflation, represented by rents and the cost
of services, is still not under control.
Yesterday's figures from Bavaria, where inflation is down to 4.2 per cent
compared with 4.4 per cent in January, showed the cost of rents and services
still rising at 6.2 per cent and 7.6 per cent. These two factors account for
more than 43 per cent of all consumer spending.
Inflation in North-Rhine Westphalia, meanwhile, dropped from 4.2 per cent to
4 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P601  Central Reserve Depositories.
