<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Dublin budget sees slippage from Emu target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRELAND'S finance minister, Mr Bertie Ahern, yesterday unveiled a 1993
budget which conceded slippage in the fiscal targets required for economic
convergence under the Maastricht plan for European monetary union. The
slippage is similar to that experienced by other EC states.
The ratio of government deficit to GDP will increase to 3.4 per cent, up
from 2.9 per cent in 1992, and while the debt/GNP ratio declined last year
to 103 per cent, it is now set to rise again in 1993 to 105 per cent as a
result of the currency crisis and increased borrowing to meet rising social
welfare bills.
Mr Ahern predicted GDP would rise by 2.5 per cent in 1993, half a point
lower than in 1992, while inflation would rise by half a point to 3.5 per
cent.
The budget calculations are based on an average sterling/punt exchange rate
of 1.02 through 1993 and a fall in interest rates of 3 per cent by the end
of the year.
Mr Ahern said: 'While I am committed to maintaining downward pressure on
public expenditure, it is clear the difficulties facing us cannot be fully
met by a combination of reduced expenditure and increased taxation this
year.
'Public expenditure will be kept under control. . However, there has to be
some increase in borrowing. An over-stringent approach would have damaging
effects on investment and employment.' The government's deficit target of
IPounds 1.033bn 'will be as close to the Maastricht deficit guideline as is
prudently possible in the present circumstances'.
The main features of the budget include increased provisions for health and
social welfare and an additional IPounds 500m capital spending programme,
part of which will be financed from EC funds.
On the revenue side, a temporary 1 per cent levy is to be put on all
personal incomes over IPounds 9,000, with a small widening of income tax
bands and a consolidation of VAT rates, leaving just two rates of 12.5 per
cent and 21 per cent.
There are also substantial excise duty increases on tobacco and cider.
Total taxation revenue is expected to rise by IPounds 126m as a result of
the budget measures.
Mr Ahern issued a strong warning to public sector unions that no further pay
increases will be contemplated in 1993, other than those already agreed.
Public sector pay will increase by 7.4 per cent this year.
Mr Ahern predicted that consumer price inflation would be 3.75 per cent this
year compared with 3 per cent last year. Unemployment would rise to 309,000
from 302,000 now.
He also said the government was willing to help Aer Lingus, the troubled
Irish carrier, saying any convincing recovery programme would be supported.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
