<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Lira feels effects of confidence vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNCERTAINTIES over the outcome of the vote of confidence on the weekend
cabinet reshuffle by the Italian prime minister, Mr Giuliano Amato,
yesterday pushed the lira to historic lows against all main currencies.
But in the highly volatile atmosphere of Italian politics, with parties
battered by the national corruption scandal and riven by internal
differences, Mr Amato yesterday appeared to have clawed back essential
support.
Both his own Socialist party and the Christian Democrats, the dominant
partners in his four-party coalition, indicated they would back him in the
vote due today.
On Tuesday elements within both parties had hinted that they might withdraw
their backing in the vote which was called by the 54-year-old prime
minister.
The prospect of the government falling without a clear replacement for the
prime minister yesterday forced the lira at one stage below the L990 level
against the D-Mark. The lira ended last week at L963 following the
resignation of the finance and health ministers which forced Sunday's
cabinet reshuffle. Since last September's currency crisis when the lira was
forced to float, the Italian currency has devalued almost 30 per cent
against the D-Mark and even further against the dollar.
The lira has now depreciated to levels which the Bank of Italy regards as
unrealistic. Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the bank's governor, commented
yesterday: 'The present quotations of the lira are obviously undervalued and
completely out of line with the state and prospectives of the Italian
economy.'
Dealers said yesterday that if the main political parties in the coalition
continued to show signs of less than whole-hearted support for the Amato
government the markets were bound to be nervous.
The authorities are concerned that further devaluation of the currency at
these levels could affect prices. Preliminary figures for February suggest
that the continuous downward trend in inflation since the second half of
1992 has been interrupted and that the first effects of devaluation are
beginning to work their way through - despite the deepening recession.
The confidence debate, which began yesterday, is due to wind up today. But
there are also moves to have the process repeated in the Senate.
Mr Amato antagonised the party rank and file by failing to consult
sufficiently over the reshuffle.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
