<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Brussels to tighten up safety at sea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday called for stricter implementation of
international rules on safety at sea to prevent a repeat of recent oil
tanker accidents.
The Commission said it would introduce legislation before the end of the
year which will oblige member states to observe minimum rules on safety,
ship maintenance and training which have already been set by the
International Maritime Organisation (IMO).
But Brussels stopped short of proposing measures which would give the
Community new maritime safety standards stricter than those already in place
under IMO regulations.
Mr Abel Matutes, EC transport commissioner, said yesterday that the main aim
was to enforce existing rules. 'There's a great deal of leeway between
adopting an international convention and actually applying it: that can lead
to a lax approach, which can lead to accidents,' he said.
The Commission also said it would be up to member states to propose and
enforce measures protecting environmentally sensitive areas from shipping.
Mr Ioannis Paleokrassas, the EC environment commissioner, said: 'There is no
map (of such areas). It isn't up to the Community to do that. This is under
national juris-diction.'
The paper published yesterday lays out 'a common policy on safe seas' and
will be submitted to EC transport ministers next month for political
backing. The Commission has been working on the paper for some time, but
speeded up publication following the oil tanker accidents earlier this year
at La Coruna, in northern Spain, and in the Shetland islands.
Mr Matutes said the introduction of any subsequent legislation would be
co-ordinated with the IMO, but he also made clear that the Commission would
press for all shipping to be subject to stricter checks.
The Braer, the tanker which broke up in the Shetlands in January, was in
transit through an international navigation lane. The Commission document
calls on IMO member states to establish 'beyond doubt' that vessels in
transit through such shipping lanes should report to coastal states about
their cargo.
Lord Sterling, chairman of P&amp;O, the British shipping company, and president
of the European Community Shipowners Association (ECSA), welcomed the report
yesterday, but warned the EC against developing 'a regional approach' to
maritime safety. 'Regional EC regimes would be both counter-productive in
terms of safety and competitively unfair for European shipowners,' he said.
The Commission said its legislative proposals would include minimum training
requirements for seafarers, minimum reporting requirements for vessels
carrying dangerous and polluting goods, common rules on technical safety
standards, and the establishment of a 'committee on safe seas'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4449 Water Transportation of Freight, NEC.
    P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Standards.
    TECH  Safety.
    GOVT  Regulations.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
