<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / ICI will announce split and Pounds 1bn rights issue today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries will today announce it intends to carry out the
biggest restructuring in UK corporate history by splitting itself into two
separately listed companies and raising Pounds 1bn through a rights issue.
The new money will be raised through a newly created company, Zeneca,
containing ICI's pharmaceutical operations, confounding the widespread
rumours that ICI itself would make the rights issue.
Following a board meeting held yesterday to finalise the details of the
demerger, the group will today say it intends to give shareholders one
Zeneca share for each ICI share they currently hold. Investors will also be
asked to subscribe for additional Zeneca shares, to raise about Pounds 1bn.
That could make the deal the second biggest rights issue in UK corporate
history, lagging behind the 1987 BP issue.
The demerger and money-raising process is likely to take a couple of months.
It will be orchestrated by SG Warburg, the group's financial adviser.
Warburg decided that the most efficient way to raise Pounds 1bn was through
Zeneca. However, before the demerger, Zeneca will inject an equivalent sum
into the rump of ICI, so that this traditional chemicals business can
prosper during the recessionary trading conditions.
Brokers are forecasting that Zeneca will make pre-tax profits of more than
Pounds 500m in the current year and that ICI profits would be less than half
that level.
ICI and its advisers are braced for criticism from some of its shareholders
about the proposal to demerge, so they have prepared a detailed marketing
campaign.
The most widespread concern in the City is that Zeneca is not quite big
enough to compete with the world's biggest drug companies.
The company has been contemplating a demerger for almost two years. In July,
it announced plans to split, but since then doubts have emerged in the City
about whether it was possible.
But ICI's executives, led by the chairman, Sir Denys Henderson, and the
chief operating officer, Mr Ronnie Hampel, have been debating the plan in
great detail with the non-executives, who include Mr Paul Volcker, former
chairman of the US Federal Reserve, and Sir Jeremy Morse, former chairman of
Lloyds Bank.
Yesterday a board meeting at the group's London headquarters gave approval
for the demerger to go ahead.
ICI will also disclose its 1992 results today. Brokers believe that its
pre-tax profits fell last year to around Pounds 550m, compared with Pounds
843m in the previous year.
However, the group is expected to maintain its dividend. Its share price
rose yesterday from Pounds 10.74 to Pounds 10.82, valuing the group at
Pounds 7.73bn.
</TEXT>
