<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Major plays down differences in first meeting with Clinton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night sought to underpin British relations with the new
US administration in a first encounter with President Bill Clinton dominated
by trade issues, the continuing crisis in Bosnia and the precarious progress
of economic reform in Russia.
As the prime minister met Mr Clinton at the White House, he brushed aside
suggestions that foreign and economic policy shifts under the new
administration would undermine the close relations established during 12
years of Republican rule.
Describing his differences with the US administration as 'tiny' compared
with their shared interests, Mr Major was clearly relieved at the White
House's apparent willingness to play down the help offered by the
Conservative party for former President George Bush's election campaign.
However, new sources of friction between Washington and London emerged with
demands from nearly 50 representatives and senators for Mr Clinton to play
an active role in the affairs of Northern Ireland.
In letters sent to the president to coincide with Mr Major's visit, the
members of Congress, including Senators Edward Kennedy and Daniel Moynihan,
referred to continuing 'human rights abuses' by British security forces in
the province.
The charge, dismissed by senior aides travelling with Mr Major, put a new
focus on President Clinton's campaign pledge to send an emissary to Ulster.
Yesterday Mr Tom Foley, speaker of the House of Representatives, said he had
not been approached by the president to carry out the task.
Mr Major set as his priority for the White House talks to persuade President
Clinton to give new momentum to the stalled Gatt world trade talks. After a
series of meetings with senior administration officials, including Mr Lloyd
Bentsen, the Treasury secretary, the prime minister emphasised to Mr Clinton
the dangers of a long extension of the deadline for 'fast-track'
congressional approval of a global trade deal.
Mr Major wants the extension planned by Mr Clinton to last no more than six,
or at most, nine months to ensure the momentum of negotiations is
maintained.
Reviewing with Mr Bentsen the agenda for Saturday's meeting of Group of
Seven finance ministers in London, Mr Major stressed that completion of the
Uruguay round of trade talks would provide the most powerful boost available
to the world economy.
Mr Major dismissed fears that Mr Clinton's recent rhetoric on trade issues
heralded a new retreat into protectionism by Washington. But he voiced
European fears that new US tariffs on steel imports and a threat to impose
higher tariffs on 'sports utility vehicles' could lead to 'tit-for-tat'
retaliation.
The planned tariff on imports of utility vehicles would threaten Land Rover
of the UK's sales to the US, even though its prime aim would be to restrict
Japanese imports.
In foreign policy discussions dominated by Bosnia and the former Soviet
Union, Mr Major suppressed private scepticism to offer backing for Mr
Clinton's plan to air-drop humanitarian supplies into eastern Bosnia. But he
stressed Britain's view that resumption of the stalled peace talks between
the warring factions in the former Yugoslav province offered the only
durable prospect for a settlement.
