<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / International Company News: Sharp fall in demand sees Deere
loss deepen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP fall in agricultural machinery sales resulted in the first-quarter
loss at Illinois-based Deere deepening to Dollars 27.6m, or 36 cents a
share.
In the same period last year, the farm equipment manufacturer with worldwide
interests suffered a loss of Dollars 19.9m or 26 cents. Deere also saw
worldwide sales drop, to Dollars 1.424bn, from Dollars 1.452bn in the first
quarter of last year.
As in the first quarter of 1992, Deere instituted a series of factory
shutdowns in an attempt to cut receivables at its equipment dealerships. The
shutdowns contributed to weak profits. The combination of reduced production
and higher first-quarter retail sales helped Deere dealers to cut
receivables by Dollars 186m during the quarter.
While Deere sold fewer pieces of equipment to its dealers, the dealers
themselves reported significantly higher retail sales in North America.
The company said demand remained very weak for agricultural equipment in
western Europe, and its worldwide equipment operations recorded a net loss
of Dollars 68.9m, compared with a Dollars 46.5m loss a year ago.
Deere's financial services and North American lawn and grounds care
equipment business improved, with each posting revenue growth in the
quarter.
'First-quarter North American retail sales levels improved over last year,
and provide a good base for the remainder of the year,' said Mr Hans
Becherer, Deere chairman. But he added that industry retail sales of
agricultural equipment in Europe 'are expected to continue downward.
European agricultural continues to experience a fundamental change which
will likely result in lower income to farmers and reduced crop production in
1993, putting further pressure on our overseas operations results.' Mr
Becherer said Deere planned selective increases in its production schedules
in 1993.
