<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / International Company News: AECI to build R300m lysine
biotechnology plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AECI, South Africa's largest chemicals group, is to build a R300m (Dollars
96m) plant producing lysine, an amino acid used in pig and poultry feed.
AECI wants to shift away from commodity chemicals towards higher value-added
chemical products and the biotechnology market.
AECI's heavy exposure to commodity chemicals has hit it hard over the past
three years. Earnings have nearly halved since 1989. Last week, AECI, in
which ICI, of the UK, has a 38 per cent stake, reported a 12 per cent drop
in attributable earnings for 1992, down to R164m.
The plant, to be built at AECI's Umbogontwini factory south of Durban, will
produce 11,000 tonnes of lysine a year.
Start-up is due for 1995. The plant's main raw material will be 30,000
tonnes a year of sugar. The world market for lysine is about 165,000 tonnes
a year.
</TEXT>
