<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / International Company News: Handelsbanken suspends pay-out
after heavy loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SVENSKA Handelsbanken has slid to a higher-than-expected 1992 operating loss
of SKr840m (Dollars 111m) and suspended the dividend on its ordinary shares
after lending losses surged 150 per cent to SKr8bn.
The deficit, which compares with a SKr2.78bn profit in 1991, is the first in
the group's recent history and follows a dramatic deterioration in its
performance in the final four months of the year.
Nevertheless, the result is substantially better than that of its main
competitors, and the group said the prospects for 1993 were brighter. In
particular, it said non-performing loans totalled SKr15.5bn at the year-end,
SKr1.5bn lower than at the end of the first eight months, the first
indication of a downward trend since Sweden's financial sector crisis began.
Mr Arne Martensson, Handelsbanken's chief executive, reaffirmed that the
group would not be looking for state bail-outs to help it manage its
problems.
The figures confirm that Handelsbanken has the best credit portfolio of the
leading Swedish banks, with a proportionally lower exposure to commercial
real estate. Its rival, Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken, last week unveiled
1992 credit losses of SKr10.9bn, problem credits of SKr28.8bn, and an
operating loss of SKr5.3bn.
Nevertheless, Handelsbanken's credit losses climbed sharply from just
SKr3.2bn in 1991 after doubling to SKr8bn, or 2.8 per cent of total lending,
from SKr3.94bn in the final four months. The group blamed high Swedish
interest rates in the autumn and the depreciation of the krona. Around 60
per cent of the bank's credit losses were connected to real estate, it said.
Handelsbanken's capital adequacy ratio was unchanged at 10.1 per cent at the
year-end.
</TEXT>
