<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Europe may get 180 TV channels: Astra satellites using
digital signals could be in place within two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 180-channel satellite television system could be available over Europe by
1995 using the latest digital technology.
Societe Europeenne des Satellites, Luxembourg-based company that operates
the Astra satellite system, has decided to launch two satellites with
digital television capacity. This gives much improved picture quality and
enables a far greater number of signals to be transmitted.
Work has already begun on the satellites which could offer unprecedented
choice to European viewers.
Mr Celso Azevedo, technical director of SES said, at the Financial Times
Cable and Satellite conference in London yesterday, that the larger number
of channels would be achieved by compressing the digital signal.
Astra already operates two 16-channel satellites carrying everything from
Sky Television to Cable News Network and Eurosport. A third satellite is now
being completed and due to be launched this spring. The fourth and fifth
Astra satellites - one due to be launched next year and the other in 1995 -
will have the digital capacity.
The SES executive said there were also proposals not yet confirmed for a
sixth Astra satellite and the company might launch more satellites taking
the total number of channels to 360.
Apart from a modest expansion in the number of conventional television
channels that could be made available the main business opportunity in such
a large number of channels lies in charging for individual films.
As many as 50 or 60 channels can be devoted, for example, to showing the top
10 films. The transmission times of films would be staggered so that the
viewer would be no more than 20 minutes from a start of any film. Digital
television could also offer wide screen television pictures.
In the US Hughes Communications, part of the Hughes Aircraft Company, is
planning to launch a 150-channel system next year using digital compression
technology.
SES insisted yesterday that it was a myth that the arrival of digital
television was 10 years off and the next 24 months would be the testing
time.
Talks had already begun with microchip manufacturers and SES believes the
special decoders needed to receive the digital pictures could be available
by 1994.
SES emphasised yesterday that if digital television was going to be a
success there would have to be agreement on a single transmission standard.
It was also vital for there to be a common encryption system. The
encryption, or scrambling system, is an essential part of subscription
television. It makes the picture unwatchable for those who have not paid.
The picture is 'unlocked' by a smart card which looks like a credit card.
Mr Pierre Meyrat, the SES director general promised yesterday that it was
still not too late to develop an economically and technically efficient path
to digital television in Europe and a wide-screen television format, in
order to give the consumer a lot more choice.
Britain can ban porn TV, Page 7
</TEXT>
