<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The billing for Life (8.00 ITV) describes it as 'a one-off live programme',
but the publicity material asserts 'the philosophy behind Life' is that it
will be compelling and sometimes controversial'. It seems that the makers
expect a series while the fierce new network controllers may have different
ideas. It sounds like precisely the sort of material we have been warned to
expect under the new ITV system: 'A global compendium of human triumphs and
tragedies', or what the Americans call 'infotainment'. We are promised
astrology and a visit to the studio by 'the world's largest venomous
spider'.
Timewatch supplies the lowdown on J. Edgar Hoover, moralistic head of the
FBI for nearly 50 years who, it now turns out, liked wearing pretty frocks
and had a long sexual relationship with the man who deputised for him (8.10
BBC2).
Mr Wroe's Virgins (BBC1 9.25) is a 4-part drama which takes the real-life
figure of John Wroe, 19th century prophet/preacher, and constructs fictional
stories around him about four of the seven virgins who provided 'comfort and
succour' in his Lancashire household.
</TEXT>
