<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour to seek social chapter vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR WILL tomorrow press its demand for another debate on Maastricht's
social chapter so that MPs can vote on a new amendment which - if passed -
the party believes could yet embarrass the government into including the
chapter in the treaty.
The opposition has new confidence that it has found a way of forcing the UK
government to choose between accepting the social chapter and being unable
to ratify the Maastricht treaty.
Comments from Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, on Monday have
encouraged both Labour and the Tory Euro-rebels to believe that a new social
chapter amendment might affect the UK government's ability to ratify. Labour
would then go on to argue that the social chapter should be included in
order for ratification to proceed.
Sir Nicholas appeared to concede that an amendment to exclude the social
protocol - which contains both the social chapter and the UK's 'opt-out'
from it - from the part of the bill extending the powers of the European
parliament would wreck the treaty.
This follows the government's conversion last week to the view that passing
the earlier Labour amendment, simply excluding the social protocol from UK
law, would not affect ratification.
When the Commons resumes detailed discussion of the Maastricht bill tomorrow
Mr George Robertson, the opposition European affairs spokesman, will ask Mr
Michael Morris, the deputy Speaker who chairs the proceedings, for an
opportunity to re-open the debate on social issues. An amendment along the
lines referred to by Sir Nicholas was tabled on Monday.
If Mr Morris does not allow MPs to talk about and vote on the new and
apparently effective Labour amendment, then the issue could be revived only
if MPs voted through any change to the bill, which would trigger an extra
stage of discussion.
Either way, the critical vote would not come for some weeks, giving time for
the government to exert pressure both on potential Tory rebels and on some
opposition parties.
All of the groupings will want to be sure of the legal position before
deciding what to do.
In particular, ministers believe that once the amendment was clearly
established as one that would wreck the treaty, the Liberal Democrats might
decide not to vote with other opposition parties.
Ministers are still confident that they will succeed in passing the bill and
emphasise that there is a majority in favour of Maastricht at Westminster,
in spite of this week's setback.
Tomorrow, when debate resumes on the planned Committee of Regions, Labour
will press for the committee's members to be elected - and may be joined by
MPs of other parties. Ministers believe, however, a Labour victory would not
jeopardise ratification.
</TEXT>
