<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Bottomley outlines plan for NHS
ranking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS VIRGINIA Bottomley, the health secretary, yesterday announced a range of
measures aimed at enabling the National Health Service internal market to
operate freely while maintaining sufficient overall control.
The government also intends to start publishing league tables of health
service performance next year, based initially on indicators including
hospital waiting times, numbers of cancelled operations and ambulance
response rates. Other indicators, based, for example, on waiting times for
consultations with specialists, will follow later.
Ministers have spent many months trying to devise a structure for regulating
the reformed service without stifling it. Under the proposals announced
yesterday both regional health authorities and regional outposts of the NHS
management executive - set up to monitor trust hospitals - will be retained.
Some trust hospital managers had argued for the abolition of regional health
authorities, fearing that they will challenge the independence of trust
boards.
Mrs Bottomley said regions must remain to handle such issues as resource
allocation, financial control, and ensuring that comprehensive services were
available for patients. They would, however, be slimmed down from an average
of 560 staff to about 200.
The health secretary, speaking at a National Association of Health
Authorities and Trusts conference in London, emphasised the importance of
purchasing authorities and GP fundholders in targeting resources, obtaining
value for money and monitoring quality.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, the health minister, is to visit all regions later this
year and assess progress on purchasing and contracting in the market.
Mrs Bottomley regards publication of the performance information, being
developed by the NHS management executive and the Audit Commission, as a
means of involving and empowering patients in the internal market.
Sir Duncan Nichol, chief executive of the NHS, said yesterday that hospital
waiting lists were a rather 'crude and one-dimensional' way of monitoring
performance.
At present there was no way for the public to see which hospitals were
meeting standards set in the government's Patient's Charter, he said.
Labour accused Mrs Bottomley of 'dithering' over the best way to control the
internal market and described her speech as a combination of muddle and
fudge.
Calling for a 'far more radical redirection of policy', Mr David Blunkett,
the shadow health secretary, said yesterday's statement did nothing to
improve NHS accountability or make the service more responsive to patients.
He later pressed home his attack in the Commons, saying the speech was an
admission the market had failed.
Why pay Pounds 8m a year to members of English NHS trusts when central
control was now to be exercised, he asked.
</TEXT>
