<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Peers criticise leasehold bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT plans for leasehold reform came under attack from all sides
yesterday, as the House of Lords began debating the bill to give certain
long-leaseholders in flats the right to join together to buy the freehold of
their block.
Criticism from peers that the proposals were too generous towards tenants
had been widely expected, but concern was also expressed by others that the
bill would not improve tenants' rights.
Tory backbench peers suggesting changes dominated the debate. As in the
Commons, the prospect of forcing government concessions will be greater
where there is an alliance of Tory backbenchers and opposition parties than
where it depends on Tory rebels alone.
Some Tory peers were clearly sensitive to the charge that they were speaking
in support of the large landlords, and underlined the impact the bill could
have on a small freeholder living in a block he or she owns. The Duke of
Westminster, London's leading landowner, listened to the debate but did not
take part.
The Lords do not pass amendments that would wreck legislation pledged in the
election. However, Lord Boardman, a Tory backbencher, emphasised that the
bill went beyond the Tory manifesto promise to improve the rights of
resident long-leaseholders.
Other Tory backbenchers pressed the case for widening the categories of
leaseholders entitled to have their leases extended. Under the plans, a
leaseholder in a block of flats which qualifies for enfranchisement is not
entitled to a lease extension, even if the tenants in the block do not buy
the freehold.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
