FT  24 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith set to spell out vote stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, is expected today to indicate the extent
to which he still backs the principle of 'one-member-one-vote' when the
party's National Executive Committee debates Labour's links with trade
unions, Ralph Atkins writes.
Mr Smith, who backed the principle during his campaign for the party
leadership last summer, will respond to a review group's interim report on
options for reducing Labour's trade union links.
A proposal for 'associate membership' for trade union members has been
opposed by Mr Neil Kinnock, former Labour leader, who supports
one-member-one-vote.
Decisions are expected to be put forward by the NEC for approval at the
party conference after consultations with party members.
The review group has proposed an end to the union block vote at conference
and the eventual introduction of one-member-one-vote for the selection of
candidates and election of the party leader. But Mr Smith faces pressure
from unions for a strong link.
