<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Fraud against companies rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VALUE of fraud perpetrated against British companies has nearly trebled
in five year to more than Pounds 468m in 1992, figures released yesterday by
accountants KPMG Peat Marwick show.
KPMG's 'fraud barometer' says total reported fraud was Pounds 1.6bn from
1987 to 1992, covering 349 separate incidents.
The figures are based on newspaper reports of fraud charges above Pounds
100,000 brought to UK courts. Any case with a not-guilty verdict is removed
from the records.
Mr Philip Haberman, a partner from the firm's forensic accounting unit, said
it was unclear whether the increase represented a jump in the number of
frauds or a rise in the level of detection.
But he said reported frauds probably represented less than 10 per cent of
total frauds. Many companies were reluctant to publicise frauds and others
did not have sufficient evidence to bring prosecutions.
He said there did not seem to be a particular increase in frauds related to
the recession, although a lot more had been revealed as a result of the
effects of the recession.
The largest amount of fraud in the last five years - nearly a third of the
total - was in the banking and finance sectors, such as forged cheques and
mortgage fraud.
A further 29 per cent were in commercial companies and 15 per cent were
against the public, including investors. Other areas included social
security and legal aid frauds.
