<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Battersea Power Station sale expected soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BATTERSEA Power Station, the derelict south London landmark, is expected to
be sold soon to a Hong Kong property family in a deal negotiated with the
banking syndicate that backed the failed scheme to turn the site into a
leisure complex.
Representatives of Mr George and Mr Victor Hwang, the brothers who are
leading negotiations on behalf of their family, said that contracts had been
exchanged between the brothers and the banks.
This was confirmed by Mr John Broome, whose company, Battersea Leisure, owns
the 31-acre site but details of how ownership would be transferred remained
unclear. He said last night that the brothers were 'buying the bank debt'
but said the brothers' statement yesterday that the deal was to acquire the
power station and site 'means the same thing'.
He said: 'The exact position is that they have bought into my syndicate bank
position and I am involved with them on that level and many other levels.'
As one of the brothers was due to fly in today to complete the deal, their
spokeswoman said that they had made no guarantees that Mr Broome would
continue to be involved in the development. She said: 'The deal has not been
finally concluded although it's very, very close.'
Mr Broome said he would be coming out of the deal clear of debts on the
site. The bank debt, he said, was probably being sold at a discount.
The listed art deco power station has been the focus of a long-running
debate about its future amid the concerns of local residents that it was in
danger of falling into an irreparable state of decay.
The announcement appears to have surprised both Wandsworth Council and
English Heritage, the government-funded conservation body, which together
have the power to veto any proposed planning alterations to the listed
building.
The Hwangs are controlling shareholders in the Hong Kong Parkview Group,
which developed and built the Hong Kong Parkview Complex in Tai Tam, one of
the colony's prime residential developments, valued at more than Pounds 1bn.
The group's interests cover property, hospitality and leisure, transport and
energy.
The spokeswoman stressed that the deal was being negotiated with the family
and not with Hong Kong Parkview, but could not give details how the sale was
being structured.
Mr Broome said he had been personally involved in the negotiations, but it
is understood that the main negotiations have been with the consortium of
banks led by Bank of America, which originally backed Mr Broome's project to
develop the power station into a leisure complex. Work on the site stopped
after the banks refused further finance when projected development costs
overshot by Pounds 60m to Pounds 230m.
</TEXT>
