<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Daf vans buy-out seeks state funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INFORMAL TALKS have started on possible government funding for the
prospective management buy-out team at the threatened Leyland Daf van plant
at Washwood Heath, Birmingham, Mr Michael Heseltine said yesterday.
Speaking in Birmingham, the trade and industry secretary said that the talks
about funding through the regional selective assistance scheme had been
between the van plant management and department officials.
He ruled out government finance to meet the day-to-day losses of the plant.
'Companies come to us for help in capital projects and it is in this context
that assistance is available,' he said.
Regional selective assistance is available under the Industrial Development
Act 1982 for companies in Britain's assisted areas.
To qualify for funding projects must cover either new ventures and
expansions which create employment, or modernisation and rationalisation
schemes which safeguard existing employment.
The administrative receivers for Leyland Daf said yesterday that they had
made a breakthrough in agreeing financing arrangements to allow dealers to
re-start sales to customers.
Sales have been hampered since the company collapsed into receivership three
weeks ago by legal problems over the ownership of vehicles in dealer
showrooms and in the supply pipeline.
Technically, most of the vehicles at dealerships are owned by Leyland Daf
Finance, which is not in receivership.
Leyland Daf Finance, a subsidiary of Daf Finance in the Netherlands, was
responsible before the collapse of Daf for much of the dealer stock
financing and customer hire purchase and leasing arrangements.
The UK receivers said yesterday that the arrangements would permit dealers
to continue supplying Leyland Daf vehicles to customers.
Mr David Gill, joint managing director of Leyland Daf, said that vehicles in
the supply pipeline, many of which had confirmed customer orders, could now
be sold. Dealers would be able to resume trading 'in a conventional way'.
</TEXT>
