<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / EC computer security breached by schoolboy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A SCHOOLBOY computer hacker breached security surrounding computer networks
at EC headquarters in Luxembourg, the Financial Times in London, European
medical organisations involved in research and treatment of cancer, and
universities, a court heard yesterday.
Such was Mr Paul Bedworth's level of illegal activity that he was unable to
pay his phone bill, British Telecommunications cut him off, and he then used
his mother's telephone line, Mr James Richardson, prosecuting, told
Southwark Crown Court.
Other hackers faced similar charges. Mr Richardson said Mr Bedworth, now 19,
who carried out his computer forays using a Pounds 200 microcomputer, was
caught when Leeds University set up a data line monitor after the level of
illegal activity on their system became so great genuine users could not
access it.
At one stage, claimed Mr Richardson, Mr Bedworth said he obtained access to
a Lloyds Bank computer. Another hacker replied he was not into stealing
cash.
'There is no suggestion that any of these had any part in fraud but the
effect that access was gained to banks demonstrates the dangers of what they
were doing and the nuisance value of what they were doing,' said Mr
Richardson.
Mr Bedworth pleaded not guilty to conspiracy to obtain telecommunication
services dishonestly, the unauthorised modification of computers and
unauthorised access of computer material.
Mr Karl Strickland, 22, unemployed, of Liverpool, and Mr Neil Woods, 26,
unemployed, of Oldham, admitted conspiracy to obtain telecommunication
services dishonestly and plotting in the unauthorised publication of
material under the Telecommunications Act 1984.
The trial was adjourned until today.
</TEXT>
