<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / NatWest denies free banking set to end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD ALEXANDER, chairman of National Westminster Bank, yesterday insisted
that his bank had no immediate plan to end 'free' banking for personal
customers who remain in credit.
Lord Alexander however said he supported the principle that banks should end
internal subsidies to forms of business which make a loss. One bank has
estimated that up to 80 per cent of its personal accounts operate at a loss.
Lord Alexander said at the presentation of the bank's full-year results for
1992: 'In principle, the banking industry has to aim for a situation where
it gives good services and receives a fair price with a minimum of
cross-subsidies.'
His remarks follow a warning from Sir Nicholas Goodison, president of the
British Bankers' Association, that efforts to end internal subsidies were
likely to put 'free' banking at risk.
In spite of speculation that NatWest could be the first bank to introduce
such charges, Lord Alexander said: 'We have no current plans to introduce
charges for personal customers whose accounts are in credit.'
NatWest results, Page 23
