<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / When trust is at a premium: Criticisms of how the insurance
sector tackles fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S insurers, slowly emerging from two years of the worst trading
conditions in their history, were attacked yesterday for failing to address
properly the problem of insurance fraud.
The criticism by Mr Julian Farrand, the industry's ombudsman, has
highlighted the difficulties of dealing with what has become a growing
problem during the recession.
In his annual report for 1992 Mr Farrand said: 'It does seem that insurers
may carry a measure of responsibility for encouraging fraudsters to believe
that insurance fraud is easy to get away with.'
Last year the Association of British Insurers, the industry trade body,
launched an advertising campaign in an attempt to reduce fraudulent claims,
which it said cost the industry more than Pounds 400m in 1991.
When the campaign was launched last June the association estimated that 12
per cent of claims were fraudulent. Ten per cent of claims were inflated
while 2 per cent were completely fraudulent.
Subsequently the Chartered Institute of Loss Adjusters said that at least
one in four household claims is inflated fraudulently, and advised insurance
companies to strengthen procedures for investigating claims.
Last month Mr Bev Fitzgerald, of the institute, said: 'There is a feeling
among the public that 'I'd be daft not to'.'
While acknowledging the association campaign Mr Farrand said that actions
spoke louder than words and that insurers did not always seem to 'help
themselves or their honest policyholders as much as they should'. He said
that because of the difficulty in proving fraud, many insurers were inclined
to find something 'in the small print' as a basis to reject a claim.
Mr Farrand said that it was 'negative' simply to repudiate a claim. Without
positive action by insurers, fraudsters would simply 'move on to the next
unsuspecting insurer', he said. Insurers should not 'pass the buck' to the
bureau but should investigate a case properly before allowing it to come to
the insurance ombudsman.
The bureau 'cannot be expected to support unsubstantiated accusations
against policyholders', said Mr Farrand, 'by for instance 'reading between
the lines' as some insurers put it'.
Yesterday the association said the situation was changing as a result of its
campaign and insurance companies were showing an increased determination to
prosecute for fraud.
The association said too many people did not appreciate that a successful
fraudulent claim would eventually be paid for by policyholders through
increased premiums. It said, however, insurers faced a number of practical
diffi-culties. 'Proving fraud is difficult when you are relying on trust as
the basis of the contract.'
Companies meanwhile responded to the ombudsman's accusations by stressing
the practical difficulties of proving fraud.
Royal Insurance said: 'It is true that too many people regard insurance
companies as fair game. We're aware of it but the problem is that the burden
of proof rests with us. You have to have evidence and that can be difficult
to get hold of.'
Mr Bob Scott, general manager of General Accident UK, rejected Mr Farrand's
comments and insisted that his company was making progress in tackling
fraud.
</TEXT>
