<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Gas plan 'may force prices up'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAS Consumers' Council said yesterday that prices for domestic consumers
could rise if the Monopolies and Mergers Commission forced British Gas to
sell its pipelines and storage arm as proposed by Ofgas, the industry
regulator.
Mr James Cooper, chairman of the Gas Consumers' Council, said in a letter to
the commission, which is reviewing the structure of British Gas's business:
'The council is not convinced that consumers will gain more from total
divestment in the manner that Ofgas has recommended.'
The consumers' council, which represents the interests of customers, said
Ofgas's proposals threatened price stability to industry, commerce and
householders throughout Britain.
British Gas has already agreed with the Office of Fair Trading to put its
transportation division into a separate subsidiary. But Ofgas believes true
competition will not be achieved until the pipelines business is under
separate ownership.
Mr Cooper said: 'I think Ofgas runs the risk of jeopardising some of the
tremendous achievements it has made, such as the 'RPI minus 5' pricing
formula.' The tough formula restricts British Gas's price increases to 5
percentage points below the rate of inflation for the next five years, which
means price cuts when inflation falls below 5 per cent.
Mr Cooper said the council was greatly concerned about how a residual gas
trading company, acting on its own and with few assets, would maintain the
service to consumers that an integrated British Gas now provided.
The sale of the pipelines business would leave a gas trading company that
might not be able to meet its supply obligations, Mr Cooper said. 'These
changes are irreversible, it can't just be changed back if it doesn't work.'
He said he was not necessarily against the sale of the pipelines business.
'What we're trying to say is: prove to us that it's a good idea.'
Mr Cooper also said he had yet to receive any proof from Ofgas that its
proposals would benefit consumers. 'The package consumers have, which gives
British Gas a supply obligation and keeps prices low, is a good one and we
want some pretty strong proof that anything that puts that at risk will be
better for consumers.'
Ofgas, however, believes more competition means more choice for consumers.
Mr John Dorken, deputy director of Ofgas, said: 'I don't see that it
necessarily leads to an increase in prices.'
Ofgas wanted to spell out the way forward for the industry, said Mr Dorken,
and not move in a piecemeal way. 'The Gas Consumers' Council is taking a
slower, more cautious approach,' he said.
The regulator is due to make a further announcement next week about the
future of British Gas, including the way pipelines could be separated from
the rest of the company.
</TEXT>
