<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / EC says Britain can ban porn TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government has the power to take immediate action against Red Hot
Dutch, the pornographic TV channel transmitted to Britain via satellite from
Denmark, a top European Commission official said yesterday.
Mrs Colette Flesch, director-general of the EC's audio visual, information,
communication and culture group, told a Financial Times conference in
London: 'We in the Commission firmly believe that the UK authorities have
the means to suspend and stop such a broadcast.'
Red Hot Dutch, which recently changed its name to Red Hot Television,
broadcasts after midnight to a subscription-paying domestic audience. It is,
however, unlicensed in the UK although it is believed to have 25,000
subscribers around the country.
Speaking at the FT Cable and Satellite conference, Mrs Flesch said the
Commission regarded Red Hot Dutch as being effectively established in the
UK.
'So far as we are concerned the situation seems clear. It's up to the
responsible authorities (in the UK) to take whatever steps they consider
right and applicable,' she said.
The government said yesterday that it was actively exploring ways of taking
action against the pornography channel but that it did not share Mrs
Flesch's interpretation of the EC directive. If the British government
decides it has the power to take action against Red Hot Television under UK
law it could take action against those supplying the decoders and other
services in the UK.
The subscriptions and the decoders, which unscramble transmissions for
fee-paying viewers, are sold by Continental Television, a Manchester-based
company registered in the Netherlands and licensed by Continental Television
BVio, a Dutch registered channel.
Lawyers for Continental Television have written to the National Heritage
Department threatening legal action if any action is taken to suppress Red
Hot Television.
The letter argues that Community law has already decided that freedom of
communication within the Community requires that any restrictions be imposed
by the country from which broadcasts are transmitted.
Under the European directive on cross-frontier broadcasting, it was assumed
it is legal to broadcast any channel that is acceptable to the country from
which the signal originates.
Separately, Sir George Russell, chairman of the Independent Television
Commission, told the conference that an early re-advertisement of a Channel
5 licence under similar terms to last time was an option that had not been
ruled out.
</TEXT>
