<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / Boutros Ghali agrees on US air-drops to Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, LAURA SILBER, ROBERT MAUTHNER, DAVID WHITE and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BELGRADE, LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US plan to drop relief supplies into blockaded areas of eastern
Bosnia-Hercegovina appears likely to go ahead by the end of this week after
President Bill Clinton won the agreement of Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
United Nations secretary-general.
Mr Boutros Ghali, who had earlier voiced doubts about the plan, said he was
in complete agreement with Mr Clinton after a meeting yesterday at the White
House. 'There is no problem. This will be done in complete co-operation,' Mr
Boutros Ghali said.
Asked if he believed there was a danger the relief mission could lead to
escalated violence, Mr Boutros Ghali said: 'No. . . we will take all of the
precautions to avoid any kind of an escalation.'
President Clinton said that the operation he planned was 'purely
humanitarian and quite limited,' with 'no combat connotations whatever'. His
remarks appeared designed to soothe the Serbian commanders, who had warned
yesterday that the move could escalate the fighting in the country.
'The airdrop would almost certainly pave the way to the massive use of
military force and the spread of armed conflict with unforeseeable
consequences,' General Milan Gvero, the deputy commander of the Bosnian Serb
army, said.
In a strongly-worded statement, Mr Iljija Djukic, the Yugoslav foreign
minister, warned the US against violating its borders. While stressing that
Yugoslavia, now comprised of Serbia and Montenegro, shared the humanitarian
concern for besieged Moslems, Mr Djukic said: 'Yugoslavia will not hinder
the realisation of the operation, but it will not tolerate the violation of
Yugoslav territory and airspace.' He said the Yugoslav army was not involved
in the civil war in Bosnia, but feared incidents in the republic could veer
out of control.
Meanwhile, the US has informed its Nato allies that it plans to go ahead
with the air-drop towards the end of this week, following consultations
between Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, and his Nato
colleagues at a meeting in Brussels on Friday.
The White House made clear the administration wanted allied backing for the
relief effort. Though the plan has been welcomed by the UN Security Council
and most of Washington's allies - and Turkey and Holland have offered to
participate in the operation - it has caused misgivings in both the US and
some allied defence establishments.
Aviation experts warned that, if the aircraft were to fly high enough to
reduce the risk of groundfire, they would be unable to target their drops
accurately. 'You're going to get some material in the hands of good guys,
and some of it, maybe most of it, in the hands of the bad guys,' said Rear
Admiral Eugene Carroll, of the Center for Defence Information, a Washington
defence policy research group.
Pentagon officials privately acknowledge that they have themselves put
forward this argument, but have been overruled because of the
administration's desire to demonstrate support for the Bosnians, having
failed to come up with a viable alternative peace plan to that presented by
Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen.
Britain has adopted an ambivalent attitude to the US plan. While formally
welcoming it, Mr Douglas Hurd, the UK foreign secretary, yesterday said that
the RAF would not participate in an operation to drop relief supplies.
Downing Street described the US plan as 'complementary' to British
humanitarian aid efforts, using ground convoys. 'What is important is that
the US is getting into the aid operation in Bosnia,' the Foreign Office
said.
Yesterday the Bosnian Serb army said it would allow overland convoys to
deliver emergency aid to besieged Moslems. An envoy of the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees reached Tuzla after being delayed by Serb troops,
but Serb fighters yesterday stopped another UNHCR convoy in Podromanija, 38
miles north of the besieged enclave of Gorazde.
Reuter adds from New York: Lt-Gen Satish Nambiar of India will shortly
relinquish command of the 23,000-strong UN Protection Force in former
Yugoslavia and is likely to be replaced by Lt-Gen Lars-Eric Wahlgren, of
Sweden, UN sources said.
Hurd defends role, Page 10
</TEXT>
