<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / German reinsurance chief dies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DR Horst Jannott, chief executive of Munchener Ruckversicherung, the world's
largest reinsurance company, died unexpectedly on Sunday, writes David
Waller in Frankfurt.
Dr Jannott joined Munich Re in 1954 and has been chief executive since 1969,
only the sixth chief executive since the company was founded in 1880. Gross
premium at the group has grown from DM300m when he first started to nearly
DM16bn (Pounds 6.7bn) in 1991-92.
Dr Jannott, who was 65, was due to step down from his position as chief
executive on March 1 to become chairman of the company's supervisory board.
Personally self-effacing, Dr Jannott , was a central figure in German
business life, an eminence grise who was chairman of four supervisory boards
and a member of the supervisory boards of eight large companies, including
Degussa, Dresdner Bank, Hoechst, MAN, Mannesmann and Veba.
He is to be succeeded as chairman of the board of managing directors (chief
executive) at Munich Re by Dr Hans-Jurgen Schinzler, 52, Dr Jannott's
deputy, for a number of years and the group's finance director since 1981.
