<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 93 / EC and weather hit agrochemicals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POOR WEATHER and the reforms of the EC's common agricultural policy that
oblige cereal farmers to set aside 15 per cent of their land led to a
decline in west Europe's agrochemicals market in 1992.
The market, the world's largest, fell 2 per cent to Dollars 7.29bn (Pounds
5.13bn), according a report* prepared by Allan Woodburn Associates, the
specialist market research group. However, the drop was worse - at about 5
per cent - in local currencies. In real terms, including inflation, the fall
was between 9 per cent and 10 per cent.
The decline was mostly weather-related, said Mr Allan Woodburn, director. In
the summer it was too dry in southern Europe, and too wet in northern Europe
last autumn. He warned that the full impact of the CAP reforms would only be
seen during 1993. The report estimated the reforms would eventually lead to
a decline in the European market of between 15 and 20 per cent by 1996. Last
week Mr Jean-Rene Fourtou, Rhone-Poulenc's chief executive, said the fall
could be up to 30 per cent.
Fungicide manufacturers are likely to be most affected, according to the
report. Herbicide demand is expected to be less severely hit.
The European insecticides market is small and more likely to be hit by the
weather than by CAP reforms. The groups most affected by the downturn are
those with the highest proportion of turnover in Europe, according to Mr
Woodburn. These include Schering of Germany (60 per cent of sales in the
region); Rhone-Poulenc of France (51 per cent); Hoechst of Germany (42 per
cent); and Bayer of Germany (37 per cent).
The report said Ciba-Geigy remained the world market-leader. Zeneca
(turnover Dollars 1.97bn) has been overtaken for the second spot by Bayer
(Dollars 2.05bn), almost entirely because of exchange rates.
*Agrochemicals executive review. Allan Woodburn Associates, 18 Newmills
Crescent, Balerno, Edinburgh. 031 451 51 73. Pounds 325 (Dollars 645).
</TEXT>
